pitalists]]\n[[Category:Anti-consumerists]]\n[[Category:Anti-corporate activists]]\n[[Category:American anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Christian Science Monitor people]]\n[[Category:Christian anarchists]]\n[[Category:Colgate University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Critics of atheism]]\n[[Category:Harvard Divinity School alumni]]\n[[Category:Nieman Fellows]]\n[[Category:People from Schoharie, New York]]\n[[Category:People from St. Johnsbury, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian socialists]]\n[[Category:The Dallas Morning News people]]\n[[Category:The Nation (U.S. magazine) people]]\n[[Category:The New York Times writers]]\n[[Category:PEN Oakland/Josephine Miles Literary Award winners]]\n[[Category:Loomis Chaffee School alumni]]\n[[Category:RT people]]\n[[Category:Writers about religion and science]]\n", "name_user": "Iankgibson", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Hedges"}
{"title_page": "Danny Makkelie", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name            = Danny Makkelie\n| image           = 12-06-05-aut-rom-freundschaftsspiel-103.jpg\n| full_name       = Danny Desmond Makkelie\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1983|1|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Willemstad]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| caption         = Makkelie in 2012\n| death_place     = \n| years1          = 2009\u2013present\n| league1         = [[Eredivisie]]\n| role1           = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| internationalyears1 = 2011\u2013present\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n\n'''Danny Desmond Makkelie''' (born 28 January 1983) is a [[Royal Dutch Football Association|Dutch]] [[Referee (association football)|football referee]]. He has been a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]] referee since 2011 and took charge of the final of the [[2012 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]] as a [[UEFA]] Elite referee.<ref>WorldReferees. [http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=7390&contextType=bio Biography of Danny Makkelie].</ref>\n\nA former police officer in [[South Holland]], he has worked full-time for the [[Royal Dutch Football Association]] since 2010. He was selected to take part in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] as a [[video assistant referee]], including the [[2018 FIFA World Cup Final]]\n\nHe made the controversial call as the Video Assistant Referee to retake the PK in the 2019 Women's World Cup for both France-Nigeria Match and the Jamaica-Italy Match.[https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438230/#match-info]  [https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438255/#match-info]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{UEFA Elite Referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makkelie, Danny}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch football referees]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Dordrecht]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| officialname    = Danny Makkelie\n| image           = 12-06-05-aut-rom-freundschaftsspiel-103.jpg\n| fullname        = Danny Desmond Makkelie\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1983|1|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Willemstad]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| caption         = Makkelie in 2012\n| death_place     = \n| years1          = 2009\u2013present\n| league1         = [[Eredivisie]]\n| role1           = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| internationalyears1 = 2011\u2013present\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n'''Danny Desmond Makkelie''' (born 28 January 1983) is a [[Royal Dutch Football Association|Dutch]] [[Referee (association football)|football referee]]. He has been a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]] referee since 2011 and took charge of the final of the [[2012 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]] as a [[UEFA]] Elite referee.<ref>WorldReferees. [http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=7390&contextType=bio Biography of Danny Makkelie].</ref>\n\nA former police officer in [[South Holland]], he has worked full-time for the [[Royal Dutch Football Association]] since 2010. He was selected to take part in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] as a [[video assistant referee]], including the [[2018 FIFA World Cup Final]]\n\nHe made the controversial call as the Video Assistant Referee to retake the PK in the 2019 Women's World Cup for both France-Nigeria Match and the Jamaica-Italy Match.[https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438230/#match-info]  [https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438255/#match-info]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{UEFA Elite Referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makkelie, Danny}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch football referees]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Dordrecht]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:update infobox to remove article from unknown parameter category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danny_Makkelie"}
{"title_page": "Greg Maffei", "text_new": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Greg Maffei\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|05|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = Colorado, U.S.\n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education =\n| alma mater = [[Dartmouth College]]<br/>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]<ref>https://www.campaignmoney.com/political/contributions/gregory-maffei.asp?cycle=16</ref>\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n}}\n'''Greg Maffei''' (born May 24, 1960) is an American businessman. He is the president and chief executive officer of [[Liberty Media]] and the chairman of [[Live Nation Entertainment]], [[Sirius XM Holdings|Sirius XM]] and [[TripAdvisor]]. He is the chairman emeritus of [[Starz]] and [[Expedia (website)|Expedia]], as well as the former chief financial officer of [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] and [[Microsoft]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGregory B. Maffei was born on May 24, 1960.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} He received an AB from [[Dartmouth College]] and his MBA from [[Harvard Business School]], where he was a Baker Scholar.<ref name=\"libertymediabio\">{{cite web|title=MANAGEMENT|url=http://ir.libertymedia.com/management.cfm|website=Liberty Media|accessdate=June 4, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Greg - head shot 2.jpg|thumb|Gregory B. Maffei]]\n\n==Business career==\nMaffei joined [[Liberty Media]] in 2005. He serves as its president and CEO. [[Liberty Media]] owns media, communications and entertainment businesses, including subsidiaries [[Formula 1]], [[Sirius XM Holdings|Sirius XM]] and the [[Atlanta Braves]] and an interest in [[Live Nation Entertainment]]. Maffei is also President and CEO of Liberty Broadband Corporation, which consists primarily of a stake in [[Charter Communications]], and serves as Chairman and CEO of Liberty TripAdvisor, which holds a controlling interest in [[TripAdvisor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ir.tripadvisor.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1564590-16-17067&CIK=1526520|title=TripAdvisor - Definitive Proxy Statement|website=ir.tripadvisor.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>  Liberty  Broadband and Liberty TripAdvisor were spun off from Liberty Media and Liberty Interactive, respectively, in 2014.<ref name=\"maffei2\">{{cite web|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/14/live-nation-names-gregory-b-maffei-as-chairman/?ref=topics&_r=0|title=Live Nation Names Gregory B. Maffei Chairman|last1=Sisario|first1=Ben|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>  Maffei also serves as President and CEO of GCI Liberty, whose principal assets consist of its subsidiaries [[GCI (company)|GCI]] and [[Evite]], and interests in [[Charter Communications]] and Liberty Broadband. In addition, Maffei serves as Executive Chairman of Qurate Retail, Inc., which owns digital commerce businesses, including subsidiaries [[QVC]], [[Home Shopping Network|HSN]], [[Zulily]] and the [[Cornerstone Brands]].\n\nHe also serves as chairman of the board of the Liberty-related companies, [[Live Nation Entertainment]], [[Sirius XM Holdings|Sirius XM]] and [[TripAdvisor]], and as a director of [[Charter Communications]] and [[Zillow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zillowgroup.com/leadership/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors \u2013 Zillow Group|website=www.zillowgroup.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> Maffei has been leading the team in transforming these companies to compete in the digital/mobile era alongside Chairman [[John C. Malone]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melby|first1=Caleb|title=Malone\u2019s Four Liberty Spinoffs Pay Maffei Combined $57 Million|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-23/malone-s-four-liberty-spinoffs-pay-maffei-combined-57-million|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nLiberty's stocks have continuously provided great returns for shareholders, for which Liberty Media was headlined in ''Barron\u2019s'' in October 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.barrons.com/articles/this-weekends-barrons-john-malone-may-be-better-than-buffett-best-bets-in-asia-broadcom-could-rise-20-1475303447|title=This Weekend\u2019s Barron\u2019s: John Malone May Be Better Than Buffett ~ Best Bets in Asia ~ Broadcom Could Rise 20%|access-date=2017-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Liberty Media ranked #7 in ''Fortune\u2019s'' 2019 World\u2019s Most Admired Companies in the Media & Entertainment Industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.fortune.com/worlds-most-admired-companies/list/filtered?industry=Entertainment&sortBy=industry-rank|title=The World's Most Admired Companies for 2017|website=Fortune|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-19}}</ref>\n\nPrior to joining Liberty Media, Maffei served as President and CFO of [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], Chairman, President and CEO of [[360networks]], CFO of [[Microsoft]], and Chairman of the Board of [[Expedia (website)|Expedia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ir.iac.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=912057-02-5012|title=IAC/InterActiveCorp - Current Report|website=ir.iac.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> Maffei was the Chairman of the Board of [[Starz]] and a Director of [[Barnes & Noble]], [[Citrix Systems|Citrix]], [[DirecTV|DIRECTV]], Dorling Kindersley, Electronic Arts, and [[Starbucks|Starbucks Coffee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20060307&slug=bizbriefs07|title=Maffei leaving Starbucks' board|website=The Seattle Times|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref> \n\nMaffei is a member of the [[Board of Trustees of Dartmouth College]] and Council on Foreign Relations<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~trustees/biographies/maffei.html|title=Greg Maffei|website=www.dartmouth.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-04-19}}</ref> He previously served as President of the Board of Trustees of the [[Seattle Public Library]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spl.org/locations/central-library/cen-about-the-central-library/cen-donors|title=Donors to the Central Library {{!}} The Seattle Public Library|website=www.spl.org|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaffei lives in Colorado with his wife and children.<ref>{{cite news|title=CEO Greg Maffei giving Liberty a lift|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2010/03/26/ceo-greg-maffei-giving-liberty-a-lift/|accessdate=28 April 2017|issue=Business|publisher=The Denver Post|date=March 26, 2010}}</ref>Dies 2020\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maffei, Greg}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American landowners]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:AT&T people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberty Media]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Greg Maffei\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|05|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = Colorado, U.S.\n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education =\n| alma mater = [[Dartmouth College]]<br/>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]<ref>https://www.campaignmoney.com/political/contributions/gregory-maffei.asp?cycle=16</ref>\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n}}\n'''Greg Maffei''' (born May 24, 1960) is an American businessman. He is the president and chief executive officer of [[Liberty Media]] and the chairman of [[Live Nation Entertainment]], [[Sirius XM Holdings|Sirius XM]] and [[TripAdvisor]]. He is the chairman emeritus of [[Starz]] and [[Expedia (website)|Expedia]], as well as the former chief financial officer of [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] and [[Microsoft]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGregory B. Maffei was born on May 24, 1960.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} He received an AB from [[Dartmouth College]] and his MBA from [[Harvard Business School]], where he was a Baker Scholar.<ref name=\"libertymediabio\">{{cite web|title=MANAGEMENT|url=http://ir.libertymedia.com/management.cfm|website=Liberty Media|accessdate=June 4, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Greg - head shot 2.jpg|thumb|Gregory B. Maffei]]\n\n==Business career==\nMaffei joined [[Liberty Media]] in 2005. He serves as its president and CEO. [[Liberty Media]] owns media, communications and entertainment businesses, including subsidiaries [[Formula 1]], [[Sirius XM Holdings|Sirius XM]] and the [[Atlanta Braves]] and an interest in [[Live Nation Entertainment]]. Maffei is also President and CEO of Liberty Broadband Corporation, which consists primarily of a stake in [[Charter Communications]], and serves as Chairman and CEO of Liberty TripAdvisor, which holds a controlling interest in [[TripAdvisor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ir.tripadvisor.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1564590-16-17067&CIK=1526520|title=TripAdvisor - Definitive Proxy Statement|website=ir.tripadvisor.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>  Liberty  Broadband and Liberty TripAdvisor were spun off from Liberty Media and Liberty Interactive, respectively, in 2014.<ref name=\"maffei2\">{{cite web|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/14/live-nation-names-gregory-b-maffei-as-chairman/?ref=topics&_r=0|title=Live Nation Names Gregory B. Maffei Chairman|last1=Sisario|first1=Ben|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>  Maffei also serves as President and CEO of GCI Liberty, whose principal assets consist of its subsidiaries [[GCI (company)|GCI]] and [[Evite]], and interests in [[Charter Communications]] and Liberty Broadband. In addition, Maffei serves as Executive Chairman of Qurate Retail, Inc., which owns digital commerce businesses, including subsidiaries [[QVC]], [[Home Shopping Network|HSN]], [[Zulily]] and the [[Cornerstone Brands]].\n\nHe also serves as chairman of the board of the Liberty-related companies, [[Live Nation Entertainment]], [[Sirius XM Holdings|Sirius XM]] and [[TripAdvisor]], and as a director of [[Charter Communications]] and [[Zillow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zillowgroup.com/leadership/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors \u2013 Zillow Group|website=www.zillowgroup.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> Maffei has been leading the team in transforming these companies to compete in the digital/mobile era alongside Chairman [[John C. Malone]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melby|first1=Caleb|title=Malone\u2019s Four Liberty Spinoffs Pay Maffei Combined $57 Million|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-23/malone-s-four-liberty-spinoffs-pay-maffei-combined-57-million|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nLiberty's stocks have continuously provided great returns for shareholders, for which Liberty Media was headlined in ''Barron\u2019s'' in October 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.barrons.com/articles/this-weekends-barrons-john-malone-may-be-better-than-buffett-best-bets-in-asia-broadcom-could-rise-20-1475303447|title=This Weekend\u2019s Barron\u2019s: John Malone May Be Better Than Buffett ~ Best Bets in Asia ~ Broadcom Could Rise 20%|access-date=2017-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Liberty Media ranked #7 in ''Fortune\u2019s'' 2019 World\u2019s Most Admired Companies in the Media & Entertainment Industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.fortune.com/worlds-most-admired-companies/list/filtered?industry=Entertainment&sortBy=industry-rank|title=The World's Most Admired Companies for 2017|website=Fortune|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-19}}</ref>\n\nPrior to joining Liberty Media, Maffei served as President and CFO of [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], Chairman, President and CEO of [[360networks]], CFO of [[Microsoft]], and Chairman of the Board of [[Expedia (website)|Expedia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ir.iac.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=912057-02-5012|title=IAC/InterActiveCorp - Current Report|website=ir.iac.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> Maffei was the Chairman of the Board of [[Starz]] and a Director of [[Barnes & Noble]], [[Citrix Systems|Citrix]], [[DirecTV|DIRECTV]], Dorling Kindersley, Electronic Arts, and [[Starbucks|Starbucks Coffee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20060307&slug=bizbriefs07|title=Maffei leaving Starbucks' board|website=The Seattle Times|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref> \n\nMaffei is a member of the [[Board of Trustees of Dartmouth College]] and Council on Foreign Relations<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~trustees/biographies/maffei.html|title=Greg Maffei|website=www.dartmouth.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-04-19}}</ref> He previously served as President of the Board of Trustees of the [[Seattle Public Library]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spl.org/locations/central-library/cen-about-the-central-library/cen-donors|title=Donors to the Central Library {{!}} The Seattle Public Library|website=www.spl.org|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaffei lives in Colorado with his wife and children.<ref>{{cite news|title=CEO Greg Maffei giving Liberty a lift|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2010/03/26/ceo-greg-maffei-giving-liberty-a-lift/|accessdate=28 April 2017|issue=Business|publisher=The Denver Post|date=March 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maffei, Greg}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American landowners]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:AT&T people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberty Media]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "87.62.132.203", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greg_Maffei"}
{"title_page": "Gulbarga district", "text_new": "{{About|the district|its eponymous headquarters|Gulbarga}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|date=March 2010}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2010}}\n{{original research|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Gulburga district\n| official_name                   = Kalaburagi district\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = \n| settlement_type                 = district\n| image_skyline                   = Gulbargha bodh gaya 03.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = [[Buddha Vihar, Gulbarga]]\n| nickname                        = \n| map_alt                         = \n| image_map                       = Karnataka Gulbarga locator map.svg\n| map_caption                     = Location in Karnataka\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|17.33|N|76.83|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Division\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Hyderabad-Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Gulbarga Division]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| seat_type                       = Headquarters\n| seat                            = [[Gulbarga]]\n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| leader_title                    = [[Deputy Commissioner (India)|Deputy Commissioner]]\n| leader_name                     = Sharath, IAS\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = <sup>'''\u2020'''</sup>\n| area_total_km2                  = 10951\n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 454\n| population_total                = 2,566,326\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <sup>'''\u2020'''</sup>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1              = Language\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 585101\n| area_code                       = 91 8472\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = KA-32\n| blank1_name_sec1                = No. of taluks\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 11\n| blank1_name_sec2                = [[Precipitation (meteorology)|Precipitation]]\n| blank1_info_sec2                = {{convert|777|mm|in}}\n| website                         = {{URL|kalaburagi.nic.in}}\n| footnotes                       = <sup>'''\u2020''website</sup>\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Kannada]],\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Gulbarga (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n| blank2_name_sec2                = Avg. summer temperature\n| blank2_info_sec2                = {{convert|42|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n| blank3_name_sec2                = Avg. winter temperature\n| blank3_info_sec2                = {{convert|26|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n}}\n\n'''Gulbarga/Kalaburagi district''',<ref name=census>{{cite web|title=Gulbarga city name changed |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/karnataka-belgaum-mysore-names-of-12-cities-changed-kannada/1/396366.html|website=indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> is one of the 30 [[Districts of Karnataka|districts]] of [[Karnataka]] state in southern [[India]]. [[Gulbarga]] city is the administrative headquarters of the district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2011/04/04/stories/2011040451200400.htm | location=Karnataka, India | work=The Hindu | title=City of tombs and domes | date=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThis district is situated in northern Karnataka between 76\u00b0.04' and 77\u00b0.42 east longitude, and 17\u00b0.12' and 17\u00b0.46' north latitude, covering an area of 10,951&nbsp;km\u00b2. This district is bounded on the west by [[Bijapur district, Karnataka|Bijapur district]] and [[Solapur district]] of [[Maharashtra]] state,  on the north by [[Bidar district]], [[Osmanabad district]] and [[Latur district]]of Maharashtra state, on the south by [[Yadgir district]], and on the east by [[Ranga Reddy district]] and [[Medak district]] of [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi|Telangana]] state.\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2006 the [[Ministry of Panchayati Raj]] named Gulbarga one of the country's 250 [[Poverty in India|most backward districts]] (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=brgf/> It is one of the five districts in Karnataka currently receiving funds from the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme (BRGF).<ref name=brgf>{{cite web|author=Ministry of Panchayati Raj|date=8 September 2009|title=A Note on the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development|url=http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf|accessdate=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405033402/http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf|archivedate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Places of interest ==\n\n=== Historical places ===\n* [[Sannati]], a small village, located on the banks of the [[Bhima River]] in [[Chitapur]] taluk is known for its [[Ashokan edicts]], Buddhist [[stupa]] and sole surviving image of [[Emperor Ashoka]] (r. 274\u2013232 BC) himself.<ref>{{cite web |title=When I met Emperor Ashoka in Sannathi |url=http://in.lifestyle.yahoo.com/photos/when-i-met-emperor-ashoka-in-sannathi-slideshow/sannathi-intro-slide-photo-1334294049.html |date= |publisher=Yahoo |access-date=21 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427011417/http://in.lifestyle.yahoo.com/photos/when-i-met-emperor-ashoka-in-sannathi-slideshow/sannathi-intro-slide-photo-1334294049.html |archive-date=27 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Manyakheta]], a village located on the banks of the Kagina river in [[Sedam]] taluk was the Capital city of the Rashtrakuta dynasty. This village is 40&nbsp;km southeast to the District Headquarters Gulbarga and 18&nbsp;km west to the Taluk Headquarters Sedam.\n* [[Gulbarga Fort]] built in 1347 Gulbarga's old moated fort is in a much deteriorated state, but it has a number of interesting buildings inside, including the Jama Masjid, reputed to have been built by a [[Moors|Moorish]] architect during the late 14th or early 15th century who imitated the great mosque in [[Cordoba, Spain]].<ref name=online>{{cite web |url=http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=7608 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120081854/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=7608 |archivedate=20 November 2010 }}</ref> The mosque is unique in India, with a huge dome covering the whole area, four smaller ones at the corners, and 75 smaller still all the way around. The fort itself has 15 towers. Gulbarga also has a number of imposing tombs(Haft Gumbaz) of Bahmani kings.\n\n== Geography ==\nGulbarga is situated in Deccan Plateau located at {{Coord|17.33|N|76.83|E|}}<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/19/Gulbarga.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc - Gulbarga]</ref> and the general elevation ranges from 300 to 750 meters above mean sea level. Two main rivers, Krishna and Bhima, flow in the district.\n\n==Subdivisions==\nGulbarga district presently comprises the following 11 talukas after the separation of [[Yadgir district]] from it.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/21801/yadgir-district-oct-31.html | title=Yadgir district from Oct 31| date=27 August 2009}}</ref>\n# [[Gulbarga]]\n# [[Aland, Karnataka|Aland]]\n# [[Afzalpur]]\n# [[Jevargi]]\n# [[Sedam]]\n# [[Shahabad, Gulbarga|Shahabad]]\n# [[Kalgi]]\n# [[Kamalapur, Gulbarga|Kamalapur]]\n# [[Chitapur]]\n# [[Chincholi]]\n# [[Yedrami]]\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in [[Gulbarga District]] (2011)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/religion/district/256-gulbarga.html |title = Gulbarga District Religion Data - Census 2011}}</ref>\n|label1 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value1 = 78.36\n|color1 = Orange\n|label2 = [[Islam]]\n|value2 = 19.99\n|color2 = Green\n|label3 = [[Christianity]]\n|value3 = 0.33\n|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|label4 = [[Jainism]]\n|value4 = 0.19\n|color4 = Brown\n|label5 = [[Buddhism]]\n|value5 = 0.37\n|color5 = Yellow\n|label6 = [[Sikhism]]\n|value6 = 0.03\n|color6 = DarkKhaki\n|label7 = Other\n|value7 = 0.02\n|color7 = GreenYellow\n|label8 = Not religious\n|value8 = 0.71\n|color8 = Black\n}}\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Gulbarga district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 2,566,326,<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/256-gulbarga.html | title = District Census 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223075613/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/256-gulbarga.html|archivedate=23 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> roughly equal to the nation of [[Kuwait]]<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web | author = US Directorate of Intelligence | title = Country Comparison:Population | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2119rank.html | accessdate = 1 October 2011 | quote = Kuwait 2,595,62\n }}</ref> or the US state of [[Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php|title=2010 Resident Population Data|publisher=U. S. Census Bureau|accessdate=30 September 2011| quote =Nevada 2,700,551\n }}</ref> This gives it a ranking of 162nd in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus/> The district has a population density of {{convert|\t233\t|PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}}.<ref name=districtcensus/> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001-2011 was  17.94%.<ref name=districtcensus/>\tGulbarga\thas a [[sex ratio]] of \t962\t[[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 65.65%.<ref name=districtcensus/>{{historical populations|11=1901|12=5,86,760|13=1911|14=6,40,851|15=1921|16=5,89,958|17=1931|18=6,58,151|19=1941|20=7,04,139|21=1951|22=8,06,394|23=1961|24=9,63,619|25=1971|26=12,08,007|27=1981|28=14,42,258|29=1991|30=17,86,138|31=2001|32=21,74,742|33=2011|34=25,66,326|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=middle}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Yadgir (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n* [[Gulbarga (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n1.\tGulnar K. Bosch, Islamic Art and Architecture, The New Book of Knowledge, Vol. 9P 354\n\n2.\tElisabeth Siddiqui, Islamic Art, Colorado State University.\n\n3.\tDept. of Islamic Art, The nature of Islamic art, \"Intleilbrunn Timeline of Art History\", The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, 2000.\n\n4.\tLinda Komaroff Ph.D., Curator of Islamic Art, Los Angeles County Museum of Art.\n\n5.\tGulam Yazdani, Bidar its History and Monuments, published by His Exalted Highness Nizam\u2019s Government, 1947 and reprint First Indian Edition by Motilal Banarsidass Publishers, Delhi in 1995. \n\n6.\tDr. Rehaman Patel, Bidri Art of Karnataka-A Study, Ph.D. Thesis submitted to Gulbarga University in 2009. published by Dept. of Kannada and Culture, Bangalore 2012\n\n7. Dr. Rehaman Patel, Islamic Art of North Karnataka, Young Muslim Digest, May 2015\n\n8. World's longest cannon lays unnoticed in Gulbarga fort, The New Indian Express, 3,12,2016\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Gulbarga (district)}}\n{{Commons category|Gulbarga district}}\n* [http://nammagulbarga.com Gulbargians most interactive website]\n* [http://gulbarga.nic.in Official Website of Gulbarga district]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930214358/http://www.gulbargacity.gov.in/ Official Website of Gulbarga City Corporation]\n* [http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/karnataka/districts/gulbarga.htm Map of Gulbarga district]\n\n{{Karnataka topics}}\n{{Districts of Karnataka}}\n{{Gulbarga topics}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulbarga District}}\n[[Category:Districts of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Gulbarga district| ]]\n[[Category:Minority Concentrated Districts in India]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the district|its eponymous headquarters|Gulbarga}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|date=March 2010}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2010}}\n{{original research|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Gulburga district\n| official_name                   = Kalaburagi district\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = \n| settl