e1              = Language\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 585101\n| area_code                       = 91 8472\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = KA-32\n| blank1_name_sec1                = No. of taluks\n| blank1_info_sec1                = 11\n| blank1_name_sec2                = [[Precipitation (meteorology)|Precipitation]]\n| blank1_info_sec2                = {{convert|777|mm|in}}\n| website                         = {{URL|kalaburagi.nic.in}}\n| footnotes                       = <sup>'''\u2020''website</sup>\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Kannada]],\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Gulbarga (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n| blank2_name_sec2                = Avg. summer temperature\n| blank2_info_sec2                = {{convert|42|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n| blank3_name_sec2                = Avg. winter temperature\n| blank3_info_sec2                = {{convert|26|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n}}\n\n'''Gulbarga district''', officially known as '''Kalaburagi district''',<ref name=census>{{cite web|title=Gulbarga city name changed |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/karnataka-belgaum-mysore-names-of-12-cities-changed-kannada/1/396366.html|website=indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> is one of the 30 [[Districts of Karnataka|districts]] of [[Karnataka]] state in southern [[India]]. [[Gulbarga]] city is the administrative headquarters of the district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2011/04/04/stories/2011040451200400.htm | location=Karnataka, India | work=The Hindu | title=City of tombs and domes | date=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThis district is situated in northern Karnataka between 76\u00b0.04' and 77\u00b0.42 east longitude, and 17\u00b0.12' and 17\u00b0.46' north latitude, covering an area of 10,951&nbsp;km\u00b2. This district is bounded on the west by [[Bijapur district, Karnataka|Bijapur district]] and [[Solapur district]] of [[Maharashtra]] state,  on the north by [[Bidar district]], [[Osmanabad district]] and [[Latur district]]of Maharashtra state, on the south by [[Yadgir district]], and on the east by [[Ranga Reddy district]] and [[Medak district]] of [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi|Telangana]] state.\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2006 the [[Ministry of Panchayati Raj]] named Gulbarga one of the country's 250 [[Poverty in India|most backward districts]] (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=brgf/> It is one of the five districts in Karnataka currently receiving funds from the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme (BRGF).<ref name=brgf>{{cite web|author=Ministry of Panchayati Raj|date=8 September 2009|title=A Note on the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development|url=http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf|accessdate=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405033402/http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf|archivedate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Places of interest ==\n\n=== Historical places ===\n* [[Sannati]], a small village, located on the banks of the [[Bhima River]] in [[Chitapur]] taluk is known for its [[Ashokan edicts]], Buddhist [[stupa]] and sole surviving image of [[Emperor Ashoka]] (r. 274\u2013232 BC) himself.<ref>{{cite web |title=When I met Emperor Ashoka in Sannathi |url=http://in.lifestyle.yahoo.com/photos/when-i-met-emperor-ashoka-in-sannathi-slideshow/sannathi-intro-slide-photo-1334294049.html |date= |publisher=Yahoo |access-date=21 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427011417/http://in.lifestyle.yahoo.com/photos/when-i-met-emperor-ashoka-in-sannathi-slideshow/sannathi-intro-slide-photo-1334294049.html |archive-date=27 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Manyakheta]], a village located on the banks of the Kagina river in [[Sedam]] taluk was the Capital city of the Rashtrakuta dynasty. This village is 40&nbsp;km southeast to the District Headquarters Gulbarga and 18&nbsp;km west to the Taluk Headquarters Sedam.\n* [[Gulbarga Fort]] built in 1347 Gulbarga's old moated fort is in a much deteriorated state, but it has a number of interesting buildings inside, including the Jama Masjid, reputed to have been built by a [[Moors|Moorish]] architect during the late 14th or early 15th century who imitated the great mosque in [[Cordoba, Spain]].<ref name=online>{{cite web |url=http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=7608 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120081854/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=7608 |archivedate=20 November 2010 }}</ref> The mosque is unique in India, with a huge dome covering the whole area, four smaller ones at the corners, and 75 smaller still all the way around. The fort itself has 15 towers. Gulbarga also has a number of imposing tombs(Haft Gumbaz) of Bahmani kings.\n\n== Geography ==\nGulbarga is situated in Deccan Plateau located at {{Coord|17.33|N|76.83|E|}}<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/19/Gulbarga.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc - Gulbarga]</ref> and the general elevation ranges from 300 to 750 meters above mean sea level. Two main rivers, Krishna and Bhima, flow in the district.\n\n==Subdivisions==\nGulbarga district presently comprises the following 11 talukas after the separation of [[Yadgir district]] from it.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/21801/yadgir-district-oct-31.html | title=Yadgir district from Oct 31| date=27 August 2009}}</ref>\n# [[Gulbarga]]\n# [[Aland, Karnataka|Aland]]\n# [[Afzalpur]]\n# [[Jevargi]]\n# [[Sedam]]\n# [[Shahabad, Gulbarga|Shahabad]]\n# [[Kalgi]]\n# [[Kamalapur, Gulbarga|Kamalapur]]\n# [[Chitapur]]\n# [[Chincholi]]\n# [[Yedrami]]\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in [[Gulbarga District]] (2011)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/religion/district/256-gulbarga.html |title = Gulbarga District Religion Data - Census 2011}}</ref>\n|label1 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value1 = 78.36\n|color1 = Orange\n|label2 = [[Islam]]\n|value2 = 19.99\n|color2 = Green\n|label3 = [[Christianity]]\n|value3 = 0.33\n|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|label4 = [[Jainism]]\n|value4 = 0.19\n|color4 = Brown\n|label5 = [[Buddhism]]\n|value5 = 0.37\n|color5 = Yellow\n|label6 = [[Sikhism]]\n|value6 = 0.03\n|color6 = DarkKhaki\n|label7 = Other\n|value7 = 0.02\n|color7 = GreenYellow\n|label8 = Not religious\n|value8 = 0.71\n|color8 = Black\n}}\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Gulbarga district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 2,566,326,<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/256-gulbarga.html | title = District Census 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223075613/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/256-gulbarga.html|archivedate=23 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> roughly equal to the nation of [[Kuwait]]<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web | author = US Directorate of Intelligence | title = Country Comparison:Population | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2119rank.html | accessdate = 1 October 2011 | quote = Kuwait 2,595,62\n }}</ref> or the US state of [[Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php|title=2010 Resident Population Data|publisher=U. S. Census Bureau|accessdate=30 September 2011| quote =Nevada 2,700,551\n }}</ref> This gives it a ranking of 162nd in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus/> The district has a population density of {{convert|\t233\t|PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}}.<ref name=districtcensus/> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001-2011 was  17.94%.<ref name=districtcensus/>\tGulbarga\thas a [[sex ratio]] of \t962\t[[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 65.65%.<ref name=districtcensus/>{{historical populations|11=1901|12=5,86,760|13=1911|14=6,40,851|15=1921|16=5,89,958|17=1931|18=6,58,151|19=1941|20=7,04,139|21=1951|22=8,06,394|23=1961|24=9,63,619|25=1971|26=12,08,007|27=1981|28=14,42,258|29=1991|30=17,86,138|31=2001|32=21,74,742|33=2011|34=25,66,326|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=middle}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Yadgir (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n* [[Gulbarga (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n1.\tGulnar K. Bosch, Islamic Art and Architecture, The New Book of Knowledge, Vol. 9P 354\n\n2.\tElisabeth Siddiqui, Islamic Art, Colorado State University.\n\n3.\tDept. of Islamic Art, The nature of Islamic art, \"Intleilbrunn Timeline of Art History\", The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, 2000.\n\n4.\tLinda Komaroff Ph.D., Curator of Islamic Art, Los Angeles County Museum of Art.\n\n5.\tGulam Yazdani, Bidar its History and Monuments, published by His Exalted Highness Nizam\u2019s Government, 1947 and reprint First Indian Edition by Motilal Banarsidass Publishers, Delhi in 1995. \n\n6.\tDr. Rehaman Patel, Bidri Art of Karnataka-A Study, Ph.D. Thesis submitted to Gulbarga University in 2009. published by Dept. of Kannada and Culture, Bangalore 2012\n\n7. Dr. Rehaman Patel, Islamic Art of North Karnataka, Young Muslim Digest, May 2015\n\n8. World's longest cannon lays unnoticed in Gulbarga fort, The New Indian Express, 3,12,2016\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Gulbarga (district)}}\n{{Commons ca