n|-\n|[[1980\u201381 Football League|1980\u201381]]||6||0||||||||||||||||||6||0\n|-\n|[[1981\u201382 Football League|1981\u201382]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]||0||0||||||||||||||||||0||0\n|-\n|[[1982\u201383 Football League|1982\u201383]]||1||0||||||||||||||||||1||0\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Career total\n!679||22||78||1||45||1||78||1||2||0||882||25\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''England'''\n*[[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[FIFA World Cup 1966|1966]]<ref name=\"WCUP\" />\n*[[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]]: third place (1): [[1968 UEFA European Championship |1968]]<ref name=\"EC68\" />\n\n'''[[Leeds United]]'''\n* [[Football League First Division]]: '''winner''' '''(2)''': [[1968\u201369 in English football|1968\u201369]], [[1973-74 in English football|1973\u201374]]<ref name=\"MR20\">{{cite news |last1=Richards |first1=Alex |title=Leeds and England legend tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/breaking-leeds-england-legend-norman-21846053 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Mirror Sport |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Football League Second Division]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1963-64 in English football|1963\u201364]]<ref name=\"GHIST\" />\n* [[FA Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]],<ref name=\"NFM\" /> runners-up (3): [[1965 FA Cup Final|1965]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=John |title=Red Men |date=April 2011 |publisher=Random House |page=116}}</ref> [[1970 FA Cup Final|1970]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Scott |title=1970 FA Cup final replay |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2020/mar/21/chelsea-v-leeds-united-1970-fa-cup-final-replay-live |website=Guardian |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> [[1973 FA Cup Final|1973]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Norman Hunter relives 1973 final heartbreak against Sunderland |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2015-01-02/i-wanted-to-forget-that-day-norman-hunter-relives-1973-final-heartbreak/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=ITV News |date=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Football League Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1968 Football League Cup Final|1968]]<ref name=\"MR20\" />\n* [[FA Charity Shield]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1969 FA Charity Shield|1969]],<ref name=\"BBC13\" /> runners-up (1): [[1974 FA Charity Shield|1974]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Durham |first1=Adrian |title=Is he all that? |date=October 2013 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |page=159}}</ref>\n* [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(2)''': [[1968 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1968]], [[1971 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1971]],<ref name=\"BBC13\" /> runners-up (1): [[1967 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1967]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Inter-Cities Fairs Cup 1967 |url=http://www.mightyleeds.co.uk/matches/19670830.htm |website=Mighty Leeds |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]: runners-up (1): [[1973 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1973]]<ref name=\"LLIVE\" />\n* [[European Cup]]: runners-up (1): [[1975 European Cup Final|1975]]<ref name=\"ECF75\" />\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Players' Player of the Year]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[PFA Players' Player of the Year|1973/74]]<ref name=\"NFM\" />\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: '''inductee''' '''(1)''': [[PFA Team of the Year|1973/74]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Tony |last=Lynch |title=The Official P.F.A. Footballers Heroes |year=1995 |publisher=Random House |location=London |isbn=978-0-09-179135-3}}</ref>\n*[[Football League 100 Legends]]: '''inductee''' '''(1)''': [[Football League 100 Legends|1998]]<ref name=\"BBC100\" />\n*Leeds United Player of the Year: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[List of Leeds United A.F.C. players#Player of the Year|1971]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Player of the Year |url=https://myleeds100.com/history/player-of-the-year/ |website=MyLeeds100 |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{englandstats|id=529|name=Norman Hunter}}\n*{{Soccerbase manager|id=991|name=Norman Hunter}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #0B0B3F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad 1966 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{England squad UEFA Euro 1968}}\n{{England squad 1970 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{1973\u201374 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{PFA Players' Player of the Year}}\n{{Leeds United F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Bristol City F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Football League 100 Legends}}\n{{English Football Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Barnsley F.C. managers}}\n{{Rotherham United F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Norman}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gateshead]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:1966 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1968 players]]\n[[Category:1970 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:English Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Association football player-managers]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Norman Hunter\n| image          = CharltonHunter1969.jpg\n| caption        = Hunter (right) and [[Bobby Charlton]] (left) in 1969\n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|10|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Eighton Banks]], [[Gateshead]],<br/> [[County Durham]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/norman-hunter_prs192638/person.shtml |website=EuroSport |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Centre back]]\n| youthyears1    = 1959\u20131962| youthclubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| years1         = 1962\u20131976 |clubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] |caps1 = 540 |goals1 = 18\n| years2         = 1976\u20131979 |clubs2 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]   |caps2 = 108 |goals2 = 4\n| years3         = 1979\u20131982 |clubs3 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]           |caps3 = 31  |goals3 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 679 |totalgoals = 22\n\n| nationalyears1 = 1964\u20131965|nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U23]]|nationalcaps1 = 3|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1965\u20131974 |nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]] |nationalcaps2 = 28 |nationalgoals2 = 2\n| manageryears1  = 1980\u20131984 |managerclubs1 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]\n| manageryears2  = 1985\u20131987 |managerclubs2 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]\n| manageryears3  = 1989\u20131990 |managerclubs3 = [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 England]]|}}\n}}\n'''Norman Hunter''' (29 October 1943-17 April 2020)<ref name=\"ETFF\">{{cite book |last1=O'Mara |first1=Michael |title=England: The Football Facts |date=2006 |publisher=Illustrated |isbn=9781843171881 |page=94 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LKzy8CSODHEC&q=%22norman+hunter%22+eighton+banks&dq=%22norman+hunter%22+eighton+banks&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiMmqiG993oAhXRkFwKHQVdAT8Q6AEIOTAC}}</ref><ref name=\"englandfootballonline\">{{cite web |title=England players: Norman Hunter |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersH/BioHunterN.html |website=englandfootballonline |accessdate=16 July 2018 |date=6 April 2016}}</ref> was an English former [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[England national football team|England]].\n\nHe was part of the [[1966 FIFA World Cup squads#England|1966 FIFA World Cup winning squad]], receiving a winner's medal in 2007.<ref name=worldcupmedal>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7112824.stm |title=England squad set for 1966 medals |accessdate=26 November 2007 |date=26 November 2007 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was the first winner of the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] award in 1974, and was included in the [[Football League 100 Legends]]. A tough tackling [[Defender_(association_football)#Centre-back|centre-half]] and [[Midfielder#Defensive_midfielder|defensive midfielder]], he was nicknamed \"Bites Yer Legs\" Hunter. The nickname originated from a banner held up by Leeds United fans at the [[1972 FA Cup Final]] against Arsenal; the banner simply read \"Norman bites yer legs\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Football League Greats: Norman Hunter |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2012/november/football-league-greats-norman-hunter/ |website=Football League |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>  He played 726 games in total for Leeds, scoring 21 goals.<ref name=\"BBCCOV\">{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter: Leeds United legend in hospital with coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52244115 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Leeds United==\nHunter was born in [[Eighton Banks]], [[Gateshead]] in 1943, and joined Leeds at the age of 16.<ref name=\"NFM\">{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter |url=https://www.nationalfootballmuseum.com/halloffame/norman-hunter/ |website=National Football Museum |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> He made his first-team debut in 1962, forming a partnership at the back with [[Jack Charlton]] which lasted for a decade.<ref name=\"LLIVE\">{{cite web |last1=Howe |first1=Jon |title=Leeds United Centurions: Norman Hunter |url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/leeds-united-centurions-norman-hunter-16583030 |website=Leeds Live |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Leeds were promoted to the First Division in 1964,<ref name=\"GHIST\">{{cite news |last1=Ingle |first1=Sean |last2=Murray |first2=Scott |title=The rise and fall and rise and fall of Leeds United |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/nov/26/sport.comment1 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=26 November 2003}}</ref> and Hunter picked up winner's medals as Leeds won the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], the [[UEFA Cup|Fairs Cup]] in 1968 and 1971, and the League Championship in 1969.<ref name=\"BBC13\">{{cite web |title=Warnock needs funds - Norman Hunter |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21042877 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NFM\" />  He was a consistent performer, playing 50 or more games for nine seasons in a row <ref name=\"LLIVE\" /> and playing all 42 league games in five separate seasons.<ref name=\"LUFCH\">{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter |url=http://www.ozwhitelufc.net.au/players_profiles/H/HunterN.php |website=Leeds United F.C. history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NFT\">{{NFT player|id=19676|name=Norman Hunter|accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nIn 1972, Leeds [[1972 FA Cup Final|won the FA Cup]] via a goal from [[Allan Clarke (footballer)|Allan Clarke]].<ref name=\"LUREV\">{{cite web |title=Don Revie named manager |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/26394/on-this-day-don-revie-named-player-manager |website=Leeds United F.C. |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> A famous photograph of Hunter's celebration when the goal went in has been published many times.<ref name=\"LUFCH\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter 1972 FA Cup Final photo |url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/football-1972-fa-cup-final-wembley-stadium-6th-may-leeds-news-photo/79020872?adppopup=true |website=Getty Images |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of the game, Hunter climbed the steps to the Royal box twice; once to collect his own medal, and then again to help [[Mick Jones (footballer, born 1945)|Mick Jones]] negotiate his way up and down, as Jones had been receiving treatment for a [[dislocation|dislocated]] elbow while his teammates had been getting their prizes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jones the Brave |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/arts-and-culture/jones-brave-1797785 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Yorkshire Post |date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n1973 saw defeats in two finals, as Leeds lost in the FA Cup Final to Sunderland, and then a few days later, to A.C. Milan in the European Cup Winners' Cup, a game overshadowed by rumours of match-fixing.<ref name=\"LUREV\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Westby |first1=Nick |title=Sporting Bygones: Still carrying the fight on behalf of Leeds United |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/latest-leeds-united-news/sporting-bygones-still-carrying-fight-behalf-leeds-united-after-dreams-european-glory-were-dashed-corrupt-referee-salonika-1864350 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Yorkshire Post |date=13 May 2013}}</ref> Hunter was sent off in the latter match for retaliation.<ref name=\"LLIVE\" />\n\nIn [[1973\u201374_in_English_football|the 1973\u201374 season]], Leeds started the season with a 29-match unbeaten run, which led them to the title, giving Hunter his second League winners medal.<ref name=\"BBC13\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Legends - Gunners deserve title |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/16661/legends-gunners-deserve-record |website=Leeds United FC |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> AT the end of that season, Hunter was the first winner of the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=\"NFM\" /><ref name=\"LLIVE\" />  As title holders Leeds thus entered the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] the following season, and Hunter was a member of the team that reached the [[1975 European Cup Final]], only to lose 2\u20130 to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Edwards |first1=Richard |title=Robbery, rioting and a brave Frenchman: Leeds' 1975 European Cup Final retold |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/robbery-rioting-and-brave-frenchman-leeds-1975-european-cup-final-retold |website=Four Four Two |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ECF75\">{{cite news |title=Leeds United great Norman Hunter's medal up for sale |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/1975-and-all-leeds-united-great-norman-hunters-medal-sale-622438 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Bristol City==\nAfter 540 Football League appearances<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Leeds United legend Norman Hunter in hospital |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-04-10/leeds-united-legend-norman-hunter-in-hospital-with-covid-19/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=ITV News |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> and 726 in total for Leeds, Hunter signed for Bristol City on 28 October 1976 for \u00a340,000, and remained there for three years, making 108 league appearances (122 in total) and scoring four goals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Thought with Norman Hunter |url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/thoughts-with-norman-hunter/ |website=Bristol City FC |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Barnsley==\nHunter finished his playing career with three seasons from 1979 to 1982 at Barnsley, where he was also manager from 1980 to 1984.<ref name=\"YP20\">{{cite news |last1=Rayner |first1=Stuart |title=Leeds United legend Norman Hunter in hospital |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-legend-norman-hunter-hospital-coronavirus-2535533 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Yorkshire Post |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nHunter was appointed Barnsley manager on 16 September 1980 after ex-Leeds player Allan Clarke left to take over as manager at Leeds United. That season, Hunter took Barnsley to second place in the Third Division and won promotion to Division Two.<ref name=\"YP20\" /> After a few good seasons, Barnsley started to struggle and Hunter was sacked on 8 February 1984.<ref name=\"YP20\" />  He had further managerial spells at [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] (1985 to 1987) and at [[Bradford City]] from 1989 to 1990 until retirement.<ref name=\"ITV\" />\n\n==International career==\nHunter played three games for [[England under-21 football team|England under-23]] before given his debut for the [[England national football team|England]] team in 1965 by manager [[Alf Ramsey]]. On 8 December 1965, England played [[Spain national football team |Spain]] in Madrid. Hunter came on in his first game, as a  35th minute substitute for [[Joe Baker]]. The substitution of Hunter in a midfield position allowed Ramsey to deploy both [[Bobby Charlton]] and [[Alan Ball Jr.|Alan Ball]] in more attacking roles as England won 2-0.<ref name=\"Bowler2013\">{{cite book|author=Dave Bowler|title=Winning Isn't Everything: A Biography of Sir Alf Ramsey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z7DrA426DHgC&pg=PT189|date=30 May 2013|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-1-4091-4676-6|pages=189\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Spain 0 - 2 England |url=https://www.englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=395 |website=EnglandStats |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The existing partnership between Jack Charlton and [[Bobby Moore]] meant that he spent much of his international career as an understudy, winning 28 caps in total.<ref>{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/norman-hunter-28935/team/leeds-united/#clubmatches |website=11v11 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCCOV\" /> He was in [[1966 FIFA World Cup squads#England|the squad]] which won the 1966 [[Football World Cup|World Cup]] but did not play any games.<ref name=\"ITV\" /><ref name=\"YP20\" />\n\nHunter scored the winning goal against Spain in England's quarter-final qualifying round for the 1968 European Championships, he then started in both the 1\u20130 semi final defeat to [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] and the 2\u20130 victory over the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] in the bronze medal match.<ref name=\"EC68\">{{cite web |title=1968 European Championship 3rd place playoff |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1968/matches/round=176/match=3939/index.html |website=UEFA.com |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Tossell |first1=David |title=Alan Ball: The Man in White Boots |date=September 2017 |publisher=Hachette}}</ref> He spent a short part of the 1970 season injured but he was in [[Alf Ramsey]]'s squad for the summer's World Cup in Mexico, however his only appearance in the tournament was coming on as a late substitute in the 3\u20132 defeat by [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Memorable England World Cup substitutions |url=https://englandmemories.com/2018/02/28/six-of-the-best-memorable-england-world-cup-substitutions/ |website=England Memories |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Hunter was in the England team which needed to win their last qualifying tie for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]] in [[West Germany]]. The opposition at Wembley were [[Poland national football team|Poland]], who just needed a draw to qualify at England's expense. It was 0\u20130 when Hunter went to make a tackle, but instead trod on the ball and lost it. Poland quickly made a counterattack and scored.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Ken |title=Laying the blame at Hunter's feet |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/laying-the-blame-at-hunters-feet-1357416.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Independent |date=8 October 1996}}</ref> Allan Clarke equalised with a penalty but England could not score again, and the 1\u20131 draw saw them miss out on a place at the World Cup. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Bevan |first1=Chris |title=When Clough's 'clown' stopped England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24445822 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing and managerial career==\nHunter turned to the after-dinner circuit recounting his anecdotes, and since 1993 has worked for local station [[BBC Radio Leeds]] and [[Yorkshire Radio]] as a summariser at Leeds games.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Culley |first1=Jon |title=Where Are They Now? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/where-are-they-now-5617981.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Independent |date=9 April 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, the [[Football League]], as part of its centenary season celebrations, included Hunter on its list of [[Football League 100 Legends|100 League Legends]].<ref name=\"BBC100\">{{cite web |title=Football  Legends list in full |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/144986.stm |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHunter released his autobiography, ''Biting Talk'', in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/norman-hunter-leeds-legendary-hardman-bleeds-for-the-soul-of-his-once-great-club-50533.html|title=Norman Hunter: Leeds' legendary hardman bleeds for the soul of his|date=7 August 2004|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|1966 World Cup final]] only the 11 players on the pitch at the end of the 4\u20132 win over West Germany received medals. Following a [[The Football Association|Football Association]] led campaign to persuade [[FIFA]] to award medals to all the squad members, Hunter was presented with his winners' medal by [[Gordon Brown]] at a ceremony at [[10 Downing Street]] on 10 June 2009.<ref name=\"WCUP\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8093891.stm|title=World Cup 1966 winners honoured|date=10 June 2009|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHunter has retained close links with Leeds United and its fans, and regularly appears at Leeds matches and figures at club hosted conferences and events; the eponymous  \"Norman Hunter Suite\" is located in the West Stand at Elland Road.<ref>{{cite web |title=Norman Hunter Suite |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/hospitality/vipsuites/normanhuntersuite |website=Leeds United F.C. |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was reported that Hunter was being treated in hospital after testing positive for [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"BBCCOV\" /> On 16 April he was described as being \u201cseverely unwell\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52308907|title=Norman Hunter: Leeds legend 'fighting coronavirus hard' but 'severely unwell'|date=16 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n<ref name=\"NFT\" /><ref name=\"LUFCH\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|[[1962\u201363 Football League|1962\u201363]]||rowspan=\"15\"|[[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]||36||2||3||0||2||0||||||||||41||2\n|-\n|[[1963\u201364 Football League|1963\u201364]]||42||2||3||0||2||0||||||||||47||2\n|-\n|[[1964\u201365 Football League|1964\u201365]]||rowspan=\"13\"|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]||41||2||8||0||2||1||||||||||51||3\n|-\n|[[1965\u201366 Football League|1965\u201366]]||41||5||2||0||1||0||11||0||||||55||5\n|-\n|[[1966\u201367 Football League|1966\u201367]]||40||0||7||0||3||0||10||0||||||60||0\n|-\n|[[1967\u201368 Football League|1967\u201368]]||40||2||5||0||7||0||11||0||||||63||2\n|-\n|[[1968\u201369 Football League|1968\u201369]]||42||0||2||0||2||0||9||1||||||55||1\n|-\n|[[1969\u201370 Football League|1969\u201370]]||35||1||7||0||2||0||6||0||1||0||51||1\n|-\n|[[1970\u201371 Football League|1970\u201371]]||42||1||4||1||1||0||10||0||||||57||2\n|-\n|[[1971\u201372 Football League|1971\u201372]]||42||0||7||0||4||0||3||0||||||56||0\n|-\n|[[1972\u201373 Football League|1972\u201373]]||32||1||7||0||5||0||9||0||||||53||1\n|-\n|[[1973\u201374 Football League|1973\u201374]]||42||0||5||0||1||0||1||0||||||49||0\n|-\n|[[1974\u201375 Football League|1974\u201375]]||25||1||5||0||4||0||8||0||1||0||42||1\n|-\n|[[1975\u201376 Football League|1975\u201376]]||31||1||2||0||2||0||||||||||35||1\n|-\n|[[1976\u201377 Football League|1976\u201377]]||9||0||||||1||0||||||||||10||0\n|-\n! rowspan=1 | \n! colspan=2 | Leeds United\n!540||18||67||1||39||1||78||1||2||0||726||21\n|-\n|[[1976\u201377 Football League|1976\u201377]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]||31||0||3||0||1||0||||||||||35||0\n|-\n|[[1977\u201378 Football League|1977\u201378]]||38||3||3||0||2||0||||||||||43||3\n|-\n|[[1978\u201379 Football League|1978\u201379]]||39||1||3||0||2||0||||||||||44||1\n|-\n|[[1979\u201380 Football League|1979\u201380]]||rowspan=\"4\"|[[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]||24||0||2||0||1||0||||||||||27||0\n|-\n|[[1980\u201381 Football League|1980\u201381]]||6||0||||||||||||||||||6||0\n|-\n|[[1981\u201382 Football League|1981\u201382]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]||0||0||||||||||||||||||0||0\n|-\n|[[1982\u201383 Football League|1982\u201383]]||1||0||||||||||||||||||1||0\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Career total\n!679||22||78||1||45||1||78||1||2||0||882||25\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''England'''\n*[[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[FIFA World Cup 1966|1966]]<ref name=\"WCUP\" />\n*[[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]]: third place (1): [[1968 UEFA European Championship |1968]]<ref name=\"EC68\" />\n\n'''[[Leeds United]]'''\n* [[Football League First Division]]: '''winner''' '''(2)''': [[1968\u201369 in English football|1968\u201369]], [[1973-74 in English football|1973\u201374]]<ref name=\"MR20\">{{cite news |last1=Richards |first1=Alex |title=Leeds and England legend tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/breaking-leeds-england-legend-norman-21846053 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Mirror Sport |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Football League Second Division]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1963-64 in English football|1963\u201364]]<ref name=\"GHIST\" />\n* [[FA Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1972 FA Cup Final|1972]],<ref name=\"NFM\" /> runners-up (3): [[1965 FA Cup Final|1965]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=John |title=Red Men |date=April 2011 |publisher=Random House |page=116}}</ref> [[1970 FA Cup Final|1970]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Scott |title=1970 FA Cup final replay |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2020/mar/21/chelsea-v-leeds-united-1970-fa-cup-final-replay-live |website=Guardian |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> [[1973 FA Cup Final|1973]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Norman Hunter relives 1973 final heartbreak against Sunderland |url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2015-01-02/i-wanted-to-forget-that-day-norman-hunter-relives-1973-final-heartbreak/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=ITV News |date=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Football League Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1968 Football League Cup Final|1968]]<ref name=\"MR20\" />\n* [[FA Charity Shield]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[1969 FA Charity Shield|1969]],<ref name=\"BBC13\" /> runners-up (1): [[1974 FA Charity Shield|1974]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Durham |first1=Adrian |title=Is he all that? |date=October 2013 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |page=159}}</ref>\n* [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]: '''winner''' '''(2)''': [[1968 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1968]], [[1971 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1971]],<ref name=\"BBC13\" /> runners-up (1): [[1967 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup Final|1967]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Inter-Cities Fairs Cup 1967 |url=http://www.mightyleeds.co.uk/matches/19670830.htm |website=Mighty Leeds |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]: runners-up (1): [[1973 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1973]]<ref name=\"LLIVE\" />\n* [[European Cup]]: runners-up (1): [[1975 European Cup Final|1975]]<ref name=\"ECF75\" />\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Players' Player of the Year]]: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[PFA Players' Player of the Year|1973/74]]<ref name=\"NFM\" />\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: '''inductee''' '''(1)''': [[PFA Team of the Year|1973/74]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Tony |last=Lynch |title=The Official P.F.A. Footballers Heroes |year=1995 |publisher=Random House |location=London |isbn=978-0-09-179135-3}}</ref>\n*[[Football League 100 Legends]]: '''inductee''' '''(1)''': [[Football League 100 Legends|1998]]<ref name=\"BBC100\" />\n*Leeds United Player of the Year: '''winner''' '''(1)''': [[List of Leeds United A.F.C. players#Player of the Year|1971]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Player of the Year |url=https://myleeds100.com/history/player-of-the-year/ |website=MyLeeds100 |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{englandstats|id=529|name=Norman Hunter}}\n*{{Soccerbase manager|id=991|name=Norman Hunter}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #0B0B3F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad 1966 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{England squad UEFA Euro 1968}}\n{{England squad 1970 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{1973\u201374 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{PFA Players' Player of the Year}}\n{{Leeds United F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Bristol City F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Football League 100 Legends}}\n{{English Football Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Barnsley F.C. managers}}\n{{Rotherham United F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Norman}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gateshead]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:1966 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1968 players]]\n[[Category:1970 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:English Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Association football player-managers]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n", "name_user": "Birdofpray111", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norman_Hunter_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Ophir", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Orphir|Ophur}}\n{{About|the region mentioned in the Bible|other uses|Ophir (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Ophir''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|o\u028a|f|\u0259r}};<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/ophir \"Ophir\"]. ''[[Random House Webster's Unabridged Dictionary]]''.</ref> {{Hebrew Name|\u05d0\u05d5\u05b9\u05e4\u05b4\u05d9\u05e8|Ofir|\u02bc\u00d4p\u0304\u00eer|Aupyr}}) is a port or region mentioned in the [[Bible]], famous for its wealth. [[King Solomon]] received a cargo from Ophir every three years, [[1 Kings]] 10:22 which consisted of gold, silver, [[sandalwood]], pearls, [[ivory]], apes, and [[peacock]]s.{{sfn|Schroff, The Periplus of the Erythr\u00e6an Sea|1912|p=41}}\n\n==Biblical references==\nOphir in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 10 (the [[Table of Nations]]) is said to be the name of one of the sons of [[Joktan]].{{efn|This is also stated in ''[[1 Chronicles]] 1:22''}} The [[Books of Kings]] and [[Books of Chronicles|Chronicles]] tell of a joint three-year expedition to Ophir by King Solomon and the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] king [[Hiram I]] from [[Ezion-Geber]], a port on the [[Red Sea]], that brought back large amounts of gold, precious stones and '[[Algum|algum wood]]' and of a later failed expedition by king [[Jehoshaphat]] of Judah.{{efn|The first expedition is described in ''[[1 Kings]] 9:28; 10:11; [[1 Chronicles]] 29:4; [[2 Chronicles]] 8:18; 9:10'', the failed expedition of Jehoshaphat in ''[[1 Kings]] 22:48''}}  The famous 'gold of Ophir' is referenced in several other books of the Hebrew Bible.{{efn|''[[Book of Job]] 22:24; 28:16; [[Psalms]] 45:9; [[Isaiah]] 13:12''}} The Book of [[Book of Tobit|Tobit]]  mentions gold of Ophir will be used to pave the streets of New Jerusalem in the last days. {{efn|''[[Book of Tobit|Tobit]] 13:17''}}\n\nIn [[Septuagint]], other variants of the name are mentioned: ''\u014cphe\u00edr'', ''S\u014dph\u00edr'', ''S\u014dphe\u00edr'' and ''Souph\u00edr''.{{sfn|Mahdi, The Dispersal of Austronesian boat forms in the Indian Ocean|1999|p=154}} However, only ''\u014cphe\u00edr'' is actually Ophir rendered in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 10 as the son of Joktan. In the same passage, Sephar is rendered ''S\u014dphe\u00edr'' and not Ophir. This merely demonstrates the [[Septuagint]] transliterating very closely to the Hebrew but substituting Sephar for Ophir in some passages as Ophir migrated to Sephar. \n\nThe [[New Testament apocrypha]] book ''[[Cave of Treasures]]'' contains a passage: \"And the children of Ophir, that is, Send, appointed to be their king Lophoron, who built Ophir with stones of gold; now, all the stones that are in Ophir are of gold.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Book of The Cave of Treasures by Ephrem the Syrian: Translated from the Syriac Text of The British Museum|last=Badge|first=William|publisher=The Religious Tract Society|year=1927|isbn=|location=London|publication-date=|pages=32|translator-last=|translator-first=|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Archaeology==\nIn 1946 an [[Ostracon|inscribed pottery shard]] was found at [[Tell Qasile]] (in modern-day [[Tel Aviv]]) dating to the eighth century BC.<ref>Maisler, B., ''Two Hebrew Ostraca from Tell Qas\u00eele'', Journal of Near Eastern Studies, Vol. 10, No. 4 (Oct., 1951), p. 265 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/542173]</ref><ref>Boardman, John, ''The Prehistory of the Balkans: The Middle East and the Aegean World, Tenth to Eighth Centuries B.C., Part 1'', Cambridge University Press, 1982, p. 480 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vXljf8JqmkoC&pg=PA480]</ref> It bears, in [[Paleo-Hebrew]] script, the text \"''gold of Ophir to/for Beth-Horon [...] 30 [[shekel]]s''\"{{efn|Beth-Horon probably refers to the [[Bethoron|ancient city]] 35 km south of Tell Qasile; another interpretation is that Beth-Horon means 'the temple of Horon', (a Canaanite deity also known as Hauron), see {{harvtxt|Lipi\u0144ski|2004|p=197}}}}<ref>Kitchen, Kenneth A.; Handy, Lowell K. (ed.), ''The Age of Solomon: Scholarship at the Turn of the Millennium'', BRILL 1997, p. 144 [https://books.google.com/books?id=gam10TAOZusC&pg=PA144]</ref> The find confirms that Ophir was a place from which gold was imported.{{sfn|Lipi\u0144ski|2004|p=144}}\n\n==Theorized locations==\n===Philippines===\nIn Tomo III (1519-1522), pages 112-138, of the book ''Colecci\u00f3n general de documentos relativos a las Islas Filipinas existentes en el Archivo de Indias de Sevilla''<ref name=CGTF>{{cite book|url=http://bdh-rd.bne.es/viewer.vm?id=0000175741&page=921|last=Compa\u00f1\u00eda General de Tabacos de Filipinas|title=Colecci\u00f3n general de documentos relativos a las Islas Filipinas existentes en el Archivo de Indias de Sevilla|volume=Tomo III--Documento 98, 1520-1528|pages=112\u2013138}}</ref>, found in the [[General Archive of the Indies]] in [[Spain]], '''Document No. 98''' describes how to locate the land of Ophir. The navigational guide started from the Cape of Good Hope in Africa to India, to Burma, to Sumatra, to Moluccas, to Borneo, to Sulu, to China, then finally Ophir which is said to be the [[Philippines]]. \n\n===India===\n''A Dictionary of the Bible'' by [[Sir William Smith]], published in 1863,<ref name=\"Smith\">Smith, William, ''A dictionary of the Bible'', Hurd and Houghton, 1863 (1870), pp.1441</ref> notes the Hebrew word for parrot ''Thukki'', derived from the Classical Tamil for peacock ''Thogkai'' and Cingalese \"tokei\",<ref>[http://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionaries/eastons-bible-dictionary/peacock.html Smith's Bible Dictionary]</ref> joins other Classical Tamil words for ivory, cotton-cloth and apes preserved in the Hebrew Bible. This theory of Ophir's location in [[Tamilakkam]] is further supported by other historians.<ref>Ramaswami, Sastri, ''The Tamils and their culture'', Annamalai University, 1967, pp.16</ref><ref>Gregory, James, ''Tamil lexicography'', M. Niemeyer, 1991, pp.10</ref><ref>Fernandes, Edna, ''The last Jews of Kerala'', Portobello, 2008, pp.98</ref><ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Ninth Edition, Volume I. No Bible translation ever uses the word parrot in any context in Biblical times. \n\nThe Bible word ''Thukki'' has never been translated as parrots in any Bible translation in history.\n\nAlmug Tree\tAlmunecar\u2192\n\nALMUG or ALGUM TREE. The Hebrew words Almuggim or Algummim are translated Almug or Algum trees in our version of the Bible (see 1 Kings x. 11, 12; 2 Chron. ii. 8, and ix. 10, 11). The wood of the tree was very precious, and was brought from Ophir (probably some part of India), along with gold and precious stones, by Hiram, and was used in the formation of pillars for the temple at Jerusalem, and for the king's house; also for the inlaying of stairs, as well as for harps and psalteries. It is probably the red sandal-wood of India (Pterocarpus santalinus). This tree belongs to the natural order Leguminos\u00e6, sub-order Papilionace\u00e6. The wood is hard, heavy, close-grained, and of a fine red colour. It is different from the white fragrant sandal-wood, which is the produce of Santalum album, a tree belonging to a distinct natural order.Also see notes by George Menachery in the St. Thomas Christian Encyclopaedia of India, Vol. 2 (1973) One must also note the National Tree of the Philippines is the Narra which is a red sandalwood as well. Both India and the Philippines possess every resource of King Solomon's acquisitions. Other claims do not. \n\n</ref> The most likely location on the coast of Kerala conjectured to be Ophir is [[Poovar]] in [[Thiruvananthapuram]] District (though some Indian scholars also suggest [[Beypore]] as possible location).<ref name=\"Menon1967\">{{citation |last=Menon |first=A. Sreedhara |title=A Survey of Kerala History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N7WaZe2PBy8C |year=1967 |publisher=Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative Society &#91;Sales Department&#93;; National Book Stall |p=58}}</ref><ref name=\"Aiyangar2004\">{{citation |last=Aiyangar |first=Sakkottai Krishnaswami |title=Ancient India: Collected Essays on the Literary and Political History of Southern India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=htArUg0OMpcC&pg=PA60 |year=2004 |origyear=first published 1911 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |isbn=978-81-206-1850-3 |pages=60\u2013}}</ref>\n\nEarlier in the 19th century [[Max M\u00fcller]] and other scholars identified Ophir with [[Abhira Kingdom|Abhira]], near the [[Indus River]] in modern-day state of [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. According to Benjamin Walker Ophir is said to have been a town of the [[Abhira tribe]].<ref name=Walker>{{citation |last=Walker |first=Benjamin |title=Hindu World: An Encyclopedic Survey of Hinduism, Volume 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iGjXAAAAMAAJ |year=1968 |publisher=Allen & Unwin |p=515}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Jewish tradition]], Ophir is often associated with a place in [[India]],{{efn|Fourteenth-century biblical commentator, [[Nathanel ben Isaiah]], writes: \"''And Ophir, and Havilah, and Jobab'' (Gen. 10:29), these are the tracts of countries in the east, being those of the first [[clime]],\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Ben Isaiah |first=N.|author-link=Nethanel ben Isaiah |title=Sefer Me'or ha-Afelah |publisher=Mechon Moshe |translator=[[Yosef Qafih]] |volume= |edition= |date=1983|location=Kiryat Ono |page=74 |language=Hebrew |url= |doi= |id= |isbn= |jfm= }}</ref> and which first clime, according to [[al-Biruni]], the sub-continent of India falls entirely therein.<ref>Sunil Sharma, ''Mughal Arcadia: Persian Literature in an Indian Court'', [[Harvard University Press]]: Cambridge 2017, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qaA4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&lpg=PA66&dq=first+clime,+second+clime,+third+and+fourth+climes&source=bl&ots=XpCu9sE2sC&sig=Lfy6OILuRBRGPdt1EwoKD6-lOG4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjoqPz88Y_eAhVRalAKHaEEDecQ6AEwBHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false 66]</ref>}} named for one of the sons of [[Joktan]].<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]'' (Book 8, chapter 6, \u00a74), s.v. ''Aurea Chersonesus''</ref> The 10th-century lexicographer, [[David ben Abraham al-Fasi]], identified Ophir with Serendip, the old Persian name for [[Sri Lanka]] (aka Ceylon).<ref>Solomon Skoss (ed.), ''The Hebrew-Arabic Dictionary of the Bible, Known as `Kit\u0101b J\u0101mi\u02bf al-Alf\u0101\u1e93` (Agron) of David ben Abraham al-Fasi'', Yale University Press: New Haven 1936, vol. 1, p. 46 (Hebrew)</ref>\n\n===Africa===\nBiblical scholars, archaeologists and others have tried to determine the exact location of Ophir. [[Vasco da Gama]]'s companion [[Thom\u00e9 Lopes|Tom\u00e9 Lopes]] reasoned that Ophir would have been the ancient name for [[Great Zimbabwe]] in [[Zimbabwe]], the main center of sub-African trade in gold in the Renaissance period \u2014 though the ruins at Great Zimbabwe are now dated to the medieval era, long after Solomon is said to have lived. The identification of Ophir with [[Sofala]] in Mozambique was mentioned by [[John Milton|Milton]] in ''[[Paradise Lost]]'' (11:399-401), among many other works of literature and science.\n\nAnother, more serious, possibility is the African shore of the [[Red Sea]], with the name perhaps being derived from the [[Afar (ethnicity)|Afar]] people living in the [[Danakil desert]] ([[Ethiopia]], [[Eritrea]]) between [[Adulis]] and [[Djibouti]].\n\n[[Afri]] was a Latin name used to refer to the [[Punics|Carthaginians]], who dwelt in [[North Africa]], in modern-day [[Tunisia]]. This name, that later gave the rich [[Roman province of Africa]] and the subsequent medieval [[Ifriqiya]], are from which the name of the continent [[Africa]] is ultimately derived, seems to have referred to a native [[Ancient Libya|Libyan]] tribe originally, however, see [[Terence#Biography|Terence]] for discussion. The name is usually connected with [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] ''afar'', \"dust\", but a 1981 hypothesis<ref>[http://michel-desfayes.org/namesofcountries.html Names of countries], Decret and Fantar, 1981</ref> has asserted that it stems from the [[Berber language|Berber]] word ''ifri'' (plural ''ifran'') meaning \"cave\", in reference to cave dwellers.<ref name=\"book on ligne\">The Berbers, by Geo. Babington Michell, p 161, 1903, Journal of the Royal African Society [https://www.jstor.org/pss/714549 book on ligne]</ref> This is proposed<ref name=\"book on ligne\"/> to be the origin of ''Ophir'' as well.{{sfn|Lipi\u0144ski|2004|p=200}}\n\nHowever, this becomes difficult to prove as Africa belongs to [[Ham]] and Ophir descends from his brother [[Shem]] and never lived in Africa but in Asia. \n\n===Americas===\n\nIn a letter written in May, 1500 [[Peter Martyr d'Anghiera|Peter Martyr]] claimed that Christopher Columbus identified [[Hispaniola]] with Ophir. <ref>De orbe novo decades</ref> However, Columbus thought he was in Southeast Asia until his end. Hispaniola has never produced the volume of gold of Ophir.\n\nThe theologian [[Benito Arias Montano]] (1571) proposed finding Ophir in the name of [[Peru]], reasoning that the native Peruvians were thus descendants of Ophir and Shem.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shalev|first1=Zur|title=Sacred Geography, Antiquarianism and Visual Erudition: Benito Arias Montano and the Maps in the Antwerp Polyglot Bible|journal=Imago Mundi|date=2003|volume=55|page=71|doi=10.1080/0308569032000097495|url=http://research.haifa.ac.il/~zshalev/Articles/IMundi-2003-Montano.pdf|accessdate=2017-01-17}}</ref> Peru lacks Ophir's resources such as native ivory and peacocks and the distance challenges the three-year timeline in that era.\n\n===Solomon Islands===\nIn 1568 [[Alvaro Menda\u00f1a]] became the first European to discover the [[Solomon Islands]], and named them as such because he believed them to be Ophir.<ref>HOGBIN, H. In, ''Experiments in Civilization: The Effects of European Culture on a Native Community of the Solomon Islands'', New York: Schocken Books, 1970 (1939), pp.7-8</ref> The Solomon Islands have never been confirmed to possess large gold deposits on the scale of ancient Ophir.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Tarshish]], another Biblical location providing Solomon with riches.\n* [[Karl Mauch]], an explorer who inadvertently discovered [[Great Zimbabwe]] when searching for Ophir.\n*[[Land of Punt]]\n* [[Chryse and Argyre]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation |first=Edward |last=Lipi\u0144ski| title=Itineraria Phoenicia Studia Phoenicia 18| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLSzNfdcqfoC&pg=PA200| year=2004| publisher=Peeters Publishers| isbn=978-90-429-1344-8}}\n* {{citation |first=Waruno |last=Mahdi |chapter=The Dispersal of Austronesian boat forms in the Indian Ocean |title=Archaeology and Language III; Artefacts, languages and texts |editor1=Roger Blench |editor2=Matthew Spriggs |publisher=Routledge |year=1999 |ISBN=0-415-10054-2 |pp=144\u2013179 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h8jfBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA144 |ref={{sfnref|Mahdi, The Dispersal of Austronesian boat forms in the Indian Ocean|1999}}}}\n* {{citation |last=Schroff |first=Wifred H. |title=The Periplus of the Erythr\u00e6an Sea: Travel and Trade in the Indian Ocean |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924030139236 |year=1912 |publisher=Longmans, Green, and Company |location=New York |ref={{sfnref|Schroff, The Periplus of the Erythr\u00e6an Sea|1912}}}}\n* (fr) Quatrem\u00e8re (1861), ''M\u00e9moire sur le pays d\u2019Ophir'', in M\u00e9langes d'histoire, Ducrocq, Paris, p. 234 ([https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_yduQhgDsMgAC/page/n275 read @ Archive]).\nFor many references and a comprehensive outline of the products exported from Muziris, Ariake &c. cf. George Menachery ed. The St. Thomas Christian Encyclopaedia of India, 1973, 1982, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060928071427/http://www.nio.org/annual_reports/1993-94.pdf Onshore explorations at Sopara and Kalyan, India]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Ophir}}\n\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible places]]\n[[Category:Torah people]]\n[[Category:Lost mines]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Orphir|Ophur}}\n{{About|the region mentioned in the Bible|other uses|Ophir (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Ophir''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|o\u028a|f|\u0259r}};<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/ophir \"Ophir\"]. ''[[Random House Webster's Unabridged Dictionary]]''.</ref> {{Hebrew Name|\u05d0\u05d5\u05b9\u05e4\u05b4\u05d9\u05e8|Ofir|\u02bc\u00d4p\u0304\u00eer|Aupyr}}) is a port or region mentioned in the [[Bible]], famous for its wealth. [[King Solomon]] received a cargo from Ophir every three years, [[1 Kings]] 10:22 which consisted of gold, silver, [[sandalwood]], pearls, [[ivory]], apes, and [[peacock]]s.{{sfn|Schroff, The Periplus of the Erythr\u00e6an Sea|1912|p=41}}\n\n==Biblical references==\nOphir in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 10 (the [[Table of Nations]]) is said to be the name of one of the sons of [[Joktan]].{{efn|This is also stated in ''[[1 Chronicles]] 1:22''}} The [[Books of Kings]] and [[Books of Chronicles|Chronicles]] tell of a joint three-year expedition to Ophir by King Solomon and the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] king [[Hiram I]] from [[Ezion-Geber]], a port on the [[Red Sea]], that brought back large amounts of gold, precious stones and '[[Algum|algum wood]]' and of a later failed expedition by king [[Jehoshaphat]] of Judah.{{efn|The first expedition is described in ''[[1 Kings]] 9:28; 10:11; [[1 Chronicles]] 29:4; [[2 Chronicles]] 8:18; 9:10'', the failed expedition of Jehoshaphat in ''[[1 Kings]] 22:48''}}  The famous 'gold of Ophir' is referenced in several other books of the Hebrew Bible.{{efn|''[[Book of Job]] 22:24; 28:16; [[Psalms]] 45:9; [[Isaiah]] 13:12''}} The Book of [[Book of Tobit|Tobit]]  mentions gold of Ophir will be used to pave the streets of New Jerusalem in the last days. {{efn|''[[Book of Tobit|Tobit]] 13:17''}}\n\nIn [[Septuagint]], other variants of the name are mentioned: ''\u014cphe\u00edr'', ''S\u014dph\u00edr'', ''S\u014dphe\u00edr'' and ''Souph\u00edr''.{{sfn|Mahdi, The Dispersal of Austronesian boat forms in the Indian Ocean|1999|p=154}} However, only ''\u014cphe\u00edr'' is actually Ophir rendered in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 10 as the son of Joktan. In the same passage, Sephar is rendered ''S\u014dphe\u00edr'' and not Ophir. This merely demonstrates the [[Septuagint]] transliterating very closely to the Hebrew but substituting Sephar for Ophir in some passages as Ophir migrated to Sephar. \n\nThe [[New Testament apocrypha]] book ''[[Cave of Treasures]]'' contains a passage: \"And the children of Ophir, that is, Send, appointed to be their king Lophoron, who built Ophir with stones of gold; now, all the stones that are in Ophir are of gold.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Book of The Cave of Treasures by Ephrem the Syrian: Translated from the Syriac Text of The British Museum|last=Badge|first=William|publisher=The Religious Tract Society|year=1927|isbn=|location=London|publication-date=|pages=32|translator-last=|translator-first=|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Archaeology==\nIn 1946 an [[Ostracon|inscribed pottery shard]] was found at [[Tell Qasile]] (in modern-day [[Tel Aviv]]) dating to the eighth century BC.<ref>Maisler, B., ''Two Hebrew Ostraca from Tell Qas\u00eele'', Journal of Near Eastern Studies, Vol. 10, No. 4 (Oct., 1951), p. 265 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/542173]</ref><ref>Boardman, John, ''The Prehistory of the Balkans: The Middle East and the Aegean World, Tenth to Eighth Centuries B.C., Part 1'', Cambridge University Press, 1982, p. 480 [https://books.google.com/books?id=vXljf8JqmkoC&pg=PA480]</ref> It bears, in [[Paleo-Hebrew]] script, the text \"''gold of Ophir to/for Beth-Horon [...] 30 [[shekel]]s''\"{{efn|Beth-Horon probably refers to the [[Bethoron|ancient city]] 35 km south of Tell Qasile; another interpretation is that Beth-Horon means 'the temple of Horon', (a Canaanite deity also known as Hauron), see {{harvtxt|Lipi\u0144ski|2004|p=197}}}}<ref>Kitchen, Kenneth A.; Handy, Lowell K. (ed.), ''The Age of Solomon: Scholarship at the Turn of the Millennium'', BRILL 1997, p. 144 [https://books.google.com/books?id=gam10TAOZusC&pg=PA144]</ref> The find confirms that Ophir was a place from which gold was imported.{{sfn|Lipi\u0144ski|2004|p=144}}\n\n==Theorized locations==\n===Philippines===\nIn Tomo III (1519-1522), pages 112-138, of the book ''Colecci\u00f3n general de documentos relativos a las Islas Filipinas existentes en el Archivo de Indias de Sevilla''<ref name=CGTF>{{cite book|url=http://bdh-rd.bne.es/viewer.vm?id=0000175741&page=921|last=Compa\u00f1\u00eda General de Tabacos de Filipinas|title=Colecci\u00f3n general de documentos relativos a las Islas Filipinas existentes en el Archivo de Indias de Sevilla|volume=Tomo III--Documento 98, 1520-1528|pages=112\u2013138}}</ref>, found in the [[General Archive of the Indies]] in [[Spain]], '''Document No. 98''' describes how to locate the land of Ophir. The navigational guide started from the Cape of Good Hope in Africa to India, to Burma, to Sumatra, to Moluccas, to Borneo, to Sulu, to China, then finally Ophir which is said to be the [[Philippines]]. \n\n===India===\n''A Dictionary of the Bible'' by [[Sir William Smith]], published in 1863,<ref name=\"Smith\">Smith, William, ''A dictionary of the Bible'', Hurd and Houghton, 1863 (1870), pp.1441</ref> notes the Hebrew word for parrot ''Thukki'', derived from the Classical Tamil for peacock ''Thogkai'' and Cingalese \"tokei\",<ref>[http://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionaries/eastons-bible-dictionary/peacock.html Smith's Bible Dictionary]</ref> joins other Classical Tamil words for ivory, cotton-cloth and apes preserved in the Hebrew Bible. This theory of Ophir's location in [[Tamilakkam]] is further supported by other historians.<ref>Ramaswami, Sastri, ''The Tamils and their culture'', Annamalai University, 1967, pp.16</ref><ref>Gregory, James, ''Tamil lexicography'', M. Niemeyer, 1991, pp.10</ref><ref>Fernandes, Edna, ''The last Jews of Kerala'', Portobello, 2008, pp.98</ref><ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Ninth Edition, Volume I. No Bible translation ever uses the word parrot in any context in Biblical times.  \nAlmug Tree\tAlmunecar\u2192\n\nALMUG or ALGUM TREE. The Hebrew words Almuggim or Algummim are translated Almug or Algum trees in our version of the Bible (see 1 Kings x. 11, 12; 2 Chron. ii. 8, and ix. 10, 11). The wood of the tree was very precious, and was brought from Ophir (probably some part of India), along with gold and precious stones, by Hiram, and was used in the formation of pillars for the temple at Jerusalem, and for the king's house; also for the inlaying of stairs, as well as for harps and psalteries. It is probably the red sandal-wood of India (Pterocarpus santalinus). This tree belongs to the natural order Leguminos\u00e6, sub-order Papilionace\u00e6. The wood is hard, heavy, close-grained, and of a fine red colour. It is different from the white fragrant sandal-wood, which is the produce of Santalum album, a tree belonging to a distinct natural order.Also see notes by George Menachery in the St. Thomas Christian Encyclopaedia of India, Vol. 2 (1973) One must also note the National Tree of the Philippines is the Narra which is a red sandalwood as well. Both India and the Philippines possess every resource of King Solomon's acquisitions. Other claims do not. \n\n</ref> The most likely location on the coast of Kerala conjectured to be Ophir is [[Poovar]] in [[Thiruvananthapuram]] District (though some Indian scholars also suggest [[Beypore]] as possible location).<ref name=\"Menon1967\">{{citation |last=Menon |first=A. Sreedhara |title=A Survey of Kerala History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N7WaZe2PBy8C |year=1967 |publisher=Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative Society &#91;Sales Department&#93;; National Book Stall |p=58}}</ref><ref name=\"Aiyangar2004\">{{citation |last=Aiyangar |first=Sakkottai Krishnaswami |title=Ancient India: Collected Essays on the Literary and Political History of Southern India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=htArUg0OMpcC&pg=PA60 |year=2004 |origyear=first published 1911 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |isbn=978-81-206-1850-3 |pages=60\u2013}}</ref>\n\nEarlier in the 19th century [[Max M\u00fcller]] and other scholars identified Ophir with [[Abhira Kingdom|Abhira]], near the [[Indus River]] in modern-day state of [[Gujarat]], [[India]]. According to Benjamin Walker Ophir is said to have been a town of the [[Abhira tribe]].<ref name=Walker>{{citation |last=Walker |first=Benjamin |title=Hindu World: An Encyclopedic Survey of Hinduism, Volume 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iGjXAAAAMAAJ |year=1968 |publisher=Allen & Unwin |p=515}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Jewish tradition]], Ophir is often associated with a place in [[India]],{{efn|Fourteenth-century biblical commentator, [[Nathanel ben Isaiah]], writes: \"''And Ophir, and Havilah, and Jobab'' (Gen. 10:29), these are the tracts of countries in the east, being those of the first [[clime]],\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Ben Isaiah |first=N.|author-link=Nethanel ben Isaiah |title=Sefer Me'or ha-Afelah |publisher=Mechon Moshe |translator=[[Yosef Qafih]] |volume= |edition= |date=1983|location=Kiryat Ono |page=74 |language=Hebrew |url= |doi= |id= |isbn= |jfm= }}</ref> and which first clime, according to [[al-Biruni]], the sub-continent of India falls entirely therein.<ref>Sunil Sharma, ''Mughal Arcadia: Persian Literature in an Indian Court'', [[Harvard University Press]]: Cambridge 2017, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qaA4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&lpg=PA66&dq=first+clime,+second+clime,+third+and+fourth+climes&source=bl&ots=XpCu9sE2sC&sig=Lfy6OILuRBRGPdt1EwoKD6-lOG4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjoqPz88Y_eAhVRalAKHaEEDecQ6AEwBHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false 66]</ref>}} named for one of the sons of [[Joktan]].<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]'' (Book 8, chapter 6, \u00a74), s.v. ''Aurea Chersonesus''</ref> The 10th-century lexicographer, [[David ben Abraham al-Fasi]], identified Ophir with Serendip, the old Persian name for [[Sri Lanka]] (aka Ceylon).<ref>Solomon Skoss (ed.), ''The Hebrew-Arabic Dictionary of the Bible, Known as `Kit\u0101b J\u0101mi\u02bf al-Alf\u0101\u1e93` (Agron) of David ben Abraham al-Fasi'', Yale University Press: New Haven 1936, vol. 1, p. 46 (Hebrew)</ref> \n\n===Africa===\nBiblical scholars, archaeologists and others have tried to determine the exact location of Ophir. [[Vasco da Gama]]'s companion [[Thom\u00e9 Lopes|Tom\u00e9 Lopes]] reasoned that Ophir would have been the ancient name for [[Great Zimbabwe]] in [[Zimbabwe]], the main center of sub-African trade in gold in the Renaissance period \u2014 though the ruins at Great Zimbabwe are now dated to the medieval era, long after Solomon is said to have lived. The identification of Ophir with [[Sofala]] in Mozambique was mentioned by [[John Milton|Milton]] in ''[[Paradise Lost]]'' (11:399-401), among many other works of literature and science.\n\nAnother, more serious, possibility is the African shore of the [[Red Sea]], with the name perhaps being derived from the [[Afar (ethnicity)|Afar]] people living in the [[Danakil desert]] ([[Ethiopia]], [[Eritrea]]) between [[Adulis]] and [[Djibouti]].\n\n[[Afri]] was a Latin name used to refer to the [[Punics|Carthaginians]], who dwelt in [[North Africa]], in modern-day [[Tunisia]]. This name, that later gave the rich [[Roman province of Africa]] and the subsequent medieval [[Ifriqiya]], are from which the name of the continent [[Africa]] is ultimately derived, seems to have referred to a native [[Ancient Libya|Libyan]] tribe originally, however, see [[Terence#Biography|Terence]] for discussion. The name is usually connected with [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] ''afar'', \"dust\", but a 1981 hypothesis<ref>[http://michel-desfayes.org/namesofcountries.html Names of countries], Decret and Fantar, 1981</ref> has asserted that it stems from the [[Berber language|Berber]] word ''ifri'' (plural ''ifran'') meaning \"cave\", in reference to cave dwellers.<ref name=\"book on ligne\">The Berbers, by Geo. Babington Michell, p 161, 1903, Journal of the Royal African Society [https://www.jstor.org/pss/714549 book on ligne]</ref> This is proposed<ref name=\"book on ligne\"/> to be the origin of ''Ophir'' as well.{{sfn|Lipi\u0144ski|2004|p=200}}\n\nHowever, this becomes difficult to prove as Africa belongs to [[Ham]] and Ophir descends from his brother [[Shem]] and never lived in Africa but in Asia. \n\n===Americas===\n\nIn a letter written in May, 1500 [[Peter Martyr d'Anghiera|Peter Martyr]] claimed that Christopher Columbus identified [[Hispaniola]] with Ophir. <ref>De orbe novo decades</ref> However, Columbus thought he was in Southeast Asia until his end. Hispaniola has never produced the volume of gold of Ophir.\n\nThe theologian [[Benito Arias Montano]] (1571) proposed finding Ophir in the name of [[Peru]], reasoning that the native Peruvians were thus descendants of Ophir and Shem.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shalev|first1=Zur|title=Sacred Geography, Antiquarianism and Visual Erudition: Benito Arias Montano and the Maps in the Antwerp Polyglot Bible|journal=Imago Mundi|date=2003|volume=55|page=71|doi=10.1080/0308569032000097495|url=http://research.haifa.ac.il/~zshalev/Articles/IMundi-2003-Montano.pdf|accessdate=2017-01-17}}</ref> Peru lacks Ophir's resources such as native ivory and peacocks and the distance challenges the three-year timeline in that era.\n\n===Solomon Islands===\nIn 1568 [[Alvaro Menda\u00f1a]] became the first European to discover the [[Solomon Islands]], and named them as such because he believed them to be Ophir.<ref>HOGBIN, H. In, ''Experiments in Civilization: The Effects of European Culture on a Native Community of the Solomon Islands'', New York: Schocken Books, 1970 (1939), pp.7-8</ref> The Solomon Islands have never been confirmed to possess large gold deposits on the scale of ancient Ophir.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Tarshish]], another Biblical location providing Solomon with riches.\n* [[Karl Mauch]], an explorer who inadvertently discovered [[Great Zimbabwe]] when searching for Ophir.\n*[[Land of Punt]]\n* [[Chryse and Argyre]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation |first=Edward |last=Lipi\u0144ski| title=Itineraria Phoenicia Studia Phoenicia 18| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLSzNfdcqfoC&pg=PA200| year=2004| publisher=Peeters Publishers| isbn=978-90-429-1344-8}}\n* {{citation |first=Waruno |last=Mahdi |chapter=The Dispersal of Austronesian boat forms in the Indian Ocean |title=Archaeology and Language III; Artefacts, languages and texts |editor1=Roger Blench |editor2=Matthew Spriggs |publisher=Routledge |year=1999 |ISBN=0-415-10054-2 |pp=144\u2013179 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h8jfBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA144 |ref={{sfnref|Mahdi, The Dispersal of Austronesian boat forms in the Indian Ocean|1999}}}}\n* {{citation |last=Schroff |first=Wifred H. |title=The Periplus of the Erythr\u00e6an Sea: Travel and Trade in the Indian Ocean |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924030139236 |year=1912 |publisher=Longmans, Green, and Company |location=New York |ref={{sfnref|Schroff, The Periplus of the Erythr\u00e6an Sea|1912}}}}\n* (fr) Quatrem\u00e8re (1861), ''M\u00e9moire sur le pays d\u2019Ophir'', in M\u00e9langes d'histoire, Ducrocq, Paris, p. 234 ([https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_yduQhgDsMgAC/page/n275 read @ Archive]).\nFor many references and a comprehensive outline of the products exported from Muziris, Ariake &c. cf. George Menachery ed. The St. Thomas Christian Encyclopaedia of India, 1973, 1982, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060928071427/http://www.nio.org/annual_reports/1993-94.pdf Onshore explorations at Sopara and Kalyan, India]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Ophir}}\n\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible places]]\n[[Category:Torah people]]\n[[Category:Lost mines]]\n", "name_user": "Thegodculture", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIndia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophir"}
{"title_page": "Pop music", "text_new": "{{About|a specific music genre|popular music in general|Popular music|other uses|Pop music (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Pop song|other uses|Pop Song (disambiguation){{!}}Pop Song}}\n{{short description|Genre of popular music which originated in its modern form in the late-1950s deriving from rock and roll}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Pop\n| color = pink\n| bgcolor = #87CEEB\n| stylistic_origins = \n* [[Traditional pop music|Traditional pop]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/subgenre/traditional-pop-ma0000002961/artists  Traditional Pop, ''Allmusic.com''].  Retrieved 25 August 2016</ref>\n* [[rock and roll]]<ref name=Grove/>\n* [[Contemporary folk music|folk]]<ref name=pc1/>\n| cultural_origins = Mid-1950s,<ref name=Firth2001/> United States and United Kingdom\n| image = \n| caption = mj\n| derivatives = * [[Disco]]\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| instruments = \n| subgenrelist = List of pop music genres\n| subgenres = * [[Art pop]]\n* [[Brill Building (genre)|Brill Building]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[experimental pop]]\n* [[hypnagogic pop]]\n* [[new wave]]\n* [[operatic pop]]\n* [[orchestral pop]]\n* [[progressive pop]]\n* [[sophisti-pop]]\n* [[space age pop]]\n* [[sunshine pop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[teen pop]]\n* pop-ballad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/pop-ballad|title=Pop ballad &#124; sentimental song|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3814513|title=Genre and the Ballad|author=Seeger, Judith|year=1994|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|volume=31|issue=1/3|pages=151\u2013176|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n| fusiongenres = * [[Baroque pop]]\n* [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]]\n* [[country pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[noise pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[psychedelic pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[reggae fusion]]\n* [[smooth jazz]]\n* [[smooth soul]]\n| regional_scenes = * [[C-pop|China]]\n* [[Indian pop|India]]\n* [[Indo pop|Indonesia]]\n* [[Cantopop|Hong Kong]]\n* [[Italian popular music#Contemporary Music|Italy]]\n* [[J-pop|Japan]]\n* [[K-pop|Korea]]\n* [[Malaysian pop|Malaysia]]\n* [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]]\n* [[Moroccan pop|Morocco]]\n* [[Pakistani pop music|Pakistan]]\n* [[P-pop|Philippines]]\n* [[Russian pop|Russia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Scandinavia]]\n* [[Swedish pop music|Sweden]]\n* [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]]\n* [[Thai pop music|Thailand]]\n* [[Turkish pop music|Turkey]]\n* [[British pop music|United Kingdom]]\n* [[American pop|United States]]\n* [[V-pop|Vietnam]]\n* [[Europop|Western Europe]]\n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Avant-pop]]\n* [[pop music automation]]\n* [[poptimism]]\n* [[rock music]]\n| current_year = no\n}}\n'''Pop music''' is a genre of [[popular music]] that originated in its modern forms in the [[United States|US]] and the [[United Kingdom|UK]] during the mid-1950s.<ref name=Firth2001/> The terms \"popular music\" and \"pop music\" are often used interchangeably, although the former describes all music that is popular and includes many diverse styles. \"Pop\" and \"[[Rock music|rock]]\" were roughly synonymous terms until the late 1960s, when they became quite separated from each other.\n\nAlthough much of the music that appears on [[record chart]]s is seen as pop music, the genre is distinguished from chart music. Pop music often borrows elements from other styles such as [[urban contemporary|urban]], [[dance music|dance]], [[rock music|rock]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[country music|country]]; nevertheless, there are many key elements that define pop music. Identifying factors usually include short to medium-length songs written in a basic format (often the [[verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus structure]]), as well as common use of repeated choruses, melodic tunes and [[hook (music)|hooks]].\n\n==Definitions and etymology{{anchor|Etymology}}==\n[[File:The Beatles in America.JPG|thumb|left|The 1960s [[British Invasion]] marked a period when the US charts were inundated with British acts such as [[the Beatles]] (pictured 1964).]]\n\nDavid Hatch and Stephen Millward define pop music as \"a body of music which is distinguishable from popular, jazz, and folk musics\".<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1987), {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 1.</ref>\nAccording to [[Pete Seeger]], pop music is \"professional music which draws upon both folk music and fine arts music\".<ref name=pc1>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19745/m1/ |title=Show 1 \u2013 Play A Simple Melody: Pete Seeger on the origins of pop music}}</ref>\nAlthough pop music is seen as just the [[record chart|singles charts]], it is not the sum of all chart music. The music charts contain songs from a variety of sources, including [[classical music|classical]], [[jazz]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[novelty song]]s. As a genre, pop music is seen to exist and develop separately.<ref>R. Serge Denisoff and William L. Schurk, ''Tarnished Gold: the Record Industry Revisited'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, 3rd edn., 1986), {{ISBN|0-88738-618-0}}, pp. 2\u20133.</ref> Therefore, the term \"pop music\" may be used to describe a distinct genre, designed to appeal to all, often characterized as \"instant singles-based music aimed at teenagers\" in contrast to rock music as \"album-based music for adults\".<ref name=Firth2001/>{{refn|Musicologist Allan Moore surmises that the term \"pop music\" itself may have been popularized by [[Pop art]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan F.|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}</ref>}}\n\nPop music continuously evolves along with the term's definition. According to music writer Bill Lamb, popular music is defined as \"the music since industrialization in the 1800s that is most in line with the tastes and interests of the urban middle class.\"<ref name=\"What Is Pop Music\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-pop-music-3246980|title=What Is Pop Music?|access-date=|last = Lamb |first =Bill|website = ThoughtCo.|date = 29 September 2018 }}</ref> The term \"pop song\" was first used in 1926, in the sense of a piece of music \"having popular appeal\".<ref name=OED>J. Simpson and E. Weiner, ''Oxford English Dictionary''(Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989). {{ISBN|0-19-861186-2}}, cf. pop.</ref> Hatch and Millward indicate that many events in the history of recording in the 1920s can be seen as the birth of the modern pop music industry, including in [[country music|country]], [[blues]], and [[hillbilly music]].<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 49.</ref>\n\n[[File: Rolling stones - 11 luglio 2006 - san siro.jpg|thumb|right|''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that the term \"pop\" refers to music performed by such artists as  [[the Rolling Stones]] (pictured here in a 2006 performance).]]\n\nAccording to the website of ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians]]'', the term \"pop music\" \"originated in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in the mid-1950s as a description for [[rock and roll]] and the new youth music styles that it influenced\".<ref name=Grove>R. Middleton, et al., [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_gmo \"Pop\"], ''Grove music online'', retrieved 14 March 2010. {{Subscription required}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that while pop's \"earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience [...] since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus[ic], usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[ABBA]], etc.\"<ref>\"Pop\", [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_t237 ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music''], retrieved 9 March 2010.{{Subscription required}}</ref> ''Grove Music Online'' also states that \"[...] in the early 1960s, [the term] 'pop music' competed terminologically with [[beat music]] [in England], while in the US its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of 'rock and roll'\".<ref name=Grove/>\n\nFrom about 1967, the term \u201cpop music\u201d was increasingly used in opposition to the term [[rock music]], a division that gave generic significance to both terms.<ref name=Gloag983>Kenneth Gloag in ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-19-866212-2}}, p. 983.</ref> While rock aspired to [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]] and an expansion of the possibilities of popular music,<ref name=Gloag983/> pop was more commercial, ephemeral, and accessible.<ref name=Warner2003>T. Warner, ''Pop Music: Technology and Creativity: Trevor Horn and the Digital Revolution'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003), {{ISBN|0-7546-3132-X}}, pp.&nbsp;3\u20134.</ref> According to British musicologist [[Simon Frith]], pop music is produced \"as a matter of [[business|enterprise]] not art\", and is \"designed to appeal to everyone\" but \"doesn't come from any particular place or mark off any particular taste\". Frith adds that it is \"not driven by any significant ambition except profit and commercial reward [...] and, in musical terms, it is essentially conservative\". It is, \"provided from on high (by record companies, radio programmers, and concert promoters) rather than being made from below&nbsp;... Pop is not a [[DIY|do-it-yourself]] music but is professionally produced and packaged\".<ref name=\"Firth2001\"/> {{clear}}\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Elvis_Presley_-_TV_Radio_Mirror,_March_1957_01.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Elvis Presley]]]]\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Righteous Brothers - You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'.ogg\n | title       = im gay \u2013 \"You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'\" (1965)\n | pos         = right\n | description ={{As of|2011}}, \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" ranks as the most frequently played song in US radio history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15186967 |title=Van's Brown Eyed Girl hits the 10 million mark in US|date=5 October 2011 |work=BBC }}</ref> It is described by music writers [[Nick Logan]] and [[Bob Woffinden]] as \"the ultimate pop record\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings, Volume 2|author=Steve Sullivan|pages=101\u2013103 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2013 |isbn= 978-0-8108-8296-6 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to Frith, characteristics of pop music include an aim of appealing to a general audience, rather than to a particular sub-culture or ideology, and an emphasis on craftsmanship rather than formal \"artistic\" qualities.<ref name=Firth2001/> Music scholar Timothy Warner said it typically has an emphasis on recording, production, and technology, rather than live performance; a tendency to reflect existing trends rather than [[progressive music|progressive developments]]; and aims to encourage dancing or uses dance-oriented rhythms.<ref name=Warner2003/>\n\nThe main medium of pop music is the song, often between two and a half and three and a half minutes in length, generally marked by a consistent and noticeable [[rhythm|rhythmic element]], a mainstream style and a simple traditional [[song structure (popular music)|structure]].<ref>W. Everett, ''Expression in Pop-rock Music: A Collection of Critical and Analytical Essays'' (London: Taylor & Francis, 2000), p. 272.</ref> Common variants include the verse-chorus form and the [[thirty-two-bar form]], with a focus on [[melody|melodies]] and catchy [[hook (music)|hooks]], and a [[refrain|chorus]] that contrasts melodically, rhythmically and [[harmony|harmonically]] with the [[Verse (music)|verse]].<ref>J. Shepherd, ''Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World: Performance and production'' (Continuum, 2003), p. 508.</ref> The beat and the melodies tend to be simple, with limited harmonic accompaniment.<ref>V. Kramarz, ''The Pop Formulas: Harmonic Tools of the Hit Makers'' (Mel Bay Publications, 2007), p. 61.</ref> The lyrics of modern pop songs typically focus on simple themes&nbsp;\u2013 often love and romantic relationships&nbsp;\u2013 although there are notable exceptions.<ref name=Firth2001/>\n\n[[Harmony (music)|Harmony]] and [[chord progression]]s in pop music are often \"that of [[Classical music|classical]] European [[tonality]], only more simple-minded.\"<ref>Winkler, Peter (1978). \"Toward a theory of pop harmony\", ''In Theory Only'', 4, pp.&nbsp;3\u201326.</ref> Clich\u00e9s include the [[close and open harmony|barbershop quartet-style harmony]] (i.e. ii \u2013 V \u2013 I) and [[blues scale]]-influenced harmony.<ref>Sargeant, p. 198. cited in Winkler (1978), p. 4.</ref> There was a lessening of the influence of traditional views of the [[circle of fifths]] between the mid-1950s and the late 1970s, including less predominance for the [[dominant (music)|dominant]] [[diatonic function|function]].<ref>Winkler (1978), p. 22.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Development and influence==\n\n===Technology and media===\n\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 230\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson in 1988.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Madonna, Rotterdam, 26-8-1987.jpg\n| width2 = \n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Michael Jackson]] (left) and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (right), known respectively as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King and Queen of Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=April 17, 2013|title=Madonna Pop Art}}</ref>\n| direction = \n}}\n\nIn the 1940s improved [[microphone]] design allowed a more intimate singing style and ten or twenty years later, inexpensive and more durable 45 rpm records for singles \"revolutionized the manner in which pop has been disseminated\", which helped to move pop music to \"a record/radio/film star system\".<ref name=Buckley>D. Buckley, \"Pop\" \"II. Implications of technology\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 15 March 2010.</ref> Another technological change was the widespread availability of television in the 1950s; with televised performances, \"pop stars had to have a visual presence\".<ref name=Buckley/> In the 1960s, the introduction of inexpensive, portable [[transistor radio]]s meant that teenagers in the developed world could listen to music outside of the home.<ref name=Buckley/> By the early 1980s, the promotion of pop music had been greatly affected by the rise of music television channels like [[MTV]], which \"favoured those artists such as [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] who had a strong visual appeal\".<ref name=Buckley/>\n\n[[Multi-track recording]] (from the 1960s); and [[sampling (music)|digital sampling]] (from the 1980s) have also been utilized as methods for the creation and elaboration of pop music.<ref name=Firth2001/> During the mid-1960s, pop music made repeated forays into new sounds, styles, and techniques that inspired public discourse among its listeners. The word \"progressive\" was frequently used, and it was thought that every song and single was to be a \"progression\" from the last.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2|page=162}}</ref> [[Music journalism|Music critic]] [[Simon Reynolds]] writes that beginning with 1967, a divide would exist between \"progressive\" pop and \"mass/chart\" pop, a separation which was \"also, broadly, one between boys and girls, middle-class and working-class.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath|page=398}}</ref>\n\nThe latter half of the 20th-century included a large-scale trend in American culture in which the boundaries between art and pop music were increasingly blurred.<ref>{{cite book|pp=317, 1233|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}</ref> Between 1950 and 1970, there was a debate of pop versus art.<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\"/> Since then, certain music publications have embraced the music's legitimacy, a trend referred to as \"[[poptimism]]\".<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\">{{cite web|last1=Loss|first1=Robert|title=No Apologies: A Critique of the Rockist v. Poptimist Paradigm|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/196122-no-apologies-a-critique-of-the-rockist-v.-poptimist-paradigm/|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stylistic evolution===\n[[File:Katy_Perry_2011.jpg|thumb|left|[[Katy Perry]]'s characteristic spinning peppermint swirl dress which she wore during the California Dreams tour|alt=]]\n\nThroughout its development, pop music has absorbed influences from other genres of popular music. Early pop music drew on the [[sentimental ballad]] for its form, gained its use of vocal harmonies from [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[soul music]], instrumentation from [[jazz]] and [[rock music]], orchestration from [[classical music]], tempo from [[dance music]], backing from [[electronic music]], rhythmic elements from [[hip-hop music]], and spoken passages from [[rap music|rap]].<ref name=Firth2001>S. Frith, W. Straw, and J. Street, eds, ''[[Cambridge Companions to Music|The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013105.</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}} In 2016, a ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' study that examined over 464,000 recordings of popular music recorded between 1955 and 2010 found that since the 1960s, pop music had found less variety in pitch progressions, grown average loudness levels,<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep00521|pmid=22837813|pmc=3405292|title=Measuring the Evolution of Contemporary Western Popular Music|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=2|pages=521|year=2012|last1=Serr\u00e0|first1=Joan|last2=Corral|first2=\u00c1lvaro|last3=Bogu\u00f1\u00e1|first3=Mari\u00e1n|last4=Haro|first4=Mart\u00edn|last5=Arcos|first5=Josep Ll.}}</ref> less diverse instrumentation and recording techniques, and less timbral variety.<ref name=\"Matson\"/> ''[[Scientific American]]''{{'}}s John Matson reported that this \"seems to support the popular anecdotal observation that pop music of yore was \"better\", or at least more varied, than today's top-40 stuff\". However, he also noted that the study may not have been entirely representative of pop in each generation.<ref name=\"Matson\">[http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/is-pop-music-evolving-or-is-it-just-getting-louder/ John Matson, \"Is Pop Music Evolving, or Is It Just Getting Louder?\", ''Scientific American'', 26 July 2012]. Retrieved 30 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the majority of mainstream pop music fell in two categories: guitar, drum and bass groups or singers backed by a traditional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Arrangements\u2014A Rough Guide To Song Construction & Arrangement, Part 1 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |work=Sound on Sound |accessdate=8 May 2014 |date=October 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508082609/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> Since early in the decade, it was common for pop producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with musical form, [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6|page=45}}</ref> At the same time, pop music on radio and in both American and British film moved away from refined [[Tin Pan Alley]] to more eccentric songwriting and incorporated reverb-drenched rock guitar, symphonic strings, and horns played by groups of properly arranged and rehearsed studio musicians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/arts/music/01pupp.html?_r=0|title=Orchestral Pop, the Way It Was (More or Less)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref>  A 2019 study held by [[New York University]] in which 643 participants had to rank how familiar a pop song is to them, songs from the 1960s turned out to be the most memorable, significantly more than songs from recent years 2000 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/news/music/best-decade-pop-music/|title=The greatest decade for pop music has been revealed (according to science)|website=Smooth|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[progressive pop]] of the late 1960s, performers were typically unable to decide on the artistic content of their music.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7|page=217}}</ref> Assisted by the mid-1960s economic boom, record labels began investing in artists, giving them the freedom to experiment, and offering them limited control over their content and marketing.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} This situation declined after the late 1970s and would not reemerge until the rise of [[Internet]] stars.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} [[Indie pop]], which developed in the late 1970s, marked another departure from the glamour of contemporary pop music, with guitar bands formed on the then-novel premise that one could record and release their own music without having to procure a [[record contract]] from a major label.<ref>{{Citation|title=Twee as Fuck: The Story of Indie Pop |first=Nitsuh |last=Abebe |work=Pitchfork Media |date=24 October 2005 |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wjlLnVho?url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Latin pop]] rose in popularity in the [[United States]] during the 1950s with early rock and roll success [[Ritchie Valens]], though it truly rose to prominence during the 1970s and 1980s with the likes of [[Los Lobos]].<ref name=\"Portwood Portwood 2019\">{{cite web | last=Portwood | first=Jerry | last2=Portwood | first2=Jerry | title=Ritchie Valens Musical in the Works From Los Lobos' Louie Perez and David Hidalgo | website=Rolling Stone | date=December 12, 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/ritchie-valens-musical-los-lobos-925326/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With later [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] seeing success within pop music charts, 1990s pop successes stayed popular in both their original genres and in broader pop music. Artists like [[Selena]] saw large-scale pop music presence, and crossover appeal with fans of [[Tejano music]] trailblazers like [[Lydia Mendoza]]; likewise in other genres like [[Lorenzo Antonio]] and [[Sparx (US band)|Sparx]], who are recognized throughout [[Latin America]] as well as within their [[New Mexico music]] repertoire of [[Al Hurricane]] and [[Antonia Apodaca]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Aldama | first=A.J. | last2=Sandoval | first2=C. | last3=Garc\u00eda | first3=P.J. | title=Performing the US Latina and Latino Borderlands | publisher=Indiana University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-253-00295-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7KXaqig1YwC&pg=PA224 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | page=224}}</ref> Musicians like [[Shakira]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Demi Lovato]] seen lasting mass-appeal within pop music circles. Latin pop hit singles, like \u201c[[Macarena]]\u201d by [[Los del R\u00edo]] and \u201c[[Despacito]]\u201d by [[Luis Fonsi]] have seen record-breaking success on worldwide pop music charts.<ref name=\"Villafa\u00f1e 2017\">{{cite web | last=Villafa\u00f1e | first=Veronica | title=Still No.1, Record-Breaking 'Despacito' Ties 'Macarena' Streak On Hot 100, But Is Snubbed By MTV | website=Forbes | date=August 14, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2017/08/14/still-no-1-record-breaking-despacito-ties-macarena-streak-on-hot-100-but-is-snubbed-by-mtv/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980s are commonly remembered for an increase in the use of [[digital recording]], associated with the usage of [[synthesizer]]s, with [[synth-pop]] music and other [[electronic music|electronic]] genres featuring non-traditional instruments increasing in popularity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/29/arts/rap-music-brash-and-swaggering-enters-mainstream.html | work=The New York Times | first=Glenn | last=Collins | title=Rap Music, Brash And Swaggering, Enters Mainstream | date=1988-08-29}}</ref> By 2014, pop music worldwide had been permeated by [[electronic dance music]].<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In 2018, researchers at the [[University of California, Irvine]], concluded that pop music has become 'sadder' since the 1980s. The elements of [[happiness]] and brightness have eventually been replaced with the electronic beats making the pop music more 'sad yet danceable'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/16/sadness-in-pop-music-study|title=New study finds pop music has gotten extremely depressing but also more fun to dance to|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = The story of pop music is largely the story of the intertwining pop culture of the United States and the United Kingdom in the postwar era.\n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 [[Bob Stanley (musician)|Bob Stanley]]<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2014|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/bn2014-07.php|title=Anti-Rockism's Hall of Fame|work=[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor =\n |width = 22%\n |salign = right\n |align = right\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 89%\n}}\n\nPop music has been dominated by the American and (from the mid-1960s) British [[music industry|music industries]], whose influence has made pop music something of an international monoculture, but most regions and countries have their own form of pop music, sometimes producing local versions of wider trends, and lending them local characteristics.<ref>J. Kun, ''Audiotopia: Music, Race, and America'' (Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0-520-24424-9}}, p. 201.</ref> Some of these trends (for example [[Europop]]) have had a significant impact of the development of the genre.<ref name=Firth2002>\"Star profiles\" in S. Frith, W. Stray and J. Street, ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp. 199\u2013200.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Grove Music Online'', \"Western-derived pop styles, whether coexisting with or marginalizing distinctively local genres, have spread throughout the world and have come to constitute stylistic common denominators in global commercial music cultures\".<ref name=PManuel>P. Manuel, \"Pop. Non-Western cultures 1. Global dissemination\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 14 March 2010.</ref> Some non-Western countries, such as Japan, have developed a thriving pop music industry, most of which is devoted to Western-style pop. Japan has for several years produced a greater quantity of music than everywhere except the US.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}}<ref name=PManuel/> The spread of Western-style pop music has been interpreted variously as representing processes of Americanization, [[Radio Homogenization|homogenization]], modernization, creative appropriation, [[cultural imperialism]], or a more general process of [[globalization]].<ref name=PManuel/>\n\nIn Korea, pop music's influence has led to the birth of [[boy bands]] and [[girl groups]] which have gained overseas renown through both their music and aesthetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/yodona/2015/12/03/565f220b46163ff4308b45c9.html|title=K-Pop, la m\u00fasica y la moda 'rarita' coreana que arrasa la red|date=December 3, 2015|website=ELMUNDO}}</ref> Korean [[co-ed groups]] (mixed gender groups) have not been as successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2016/08/25/why-arent-there-many-mixed-gender-k-pop-groups|title=Why aren't there many mixed gender K-pop groups?|website=SBS PopAsia}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pop music|Music}}\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[Origins of rock and roll]]\n* [[Popular music pedagogy]]\n* [[List of popular music genres]]\n* [[History of music]]\n* [[Public domain music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno|Adorno, Theodor W.]], (1942) \"On Popular Music\", Institute of Social Research.\n* Bell, John L., (2000) ''The Singing Thing: A Case for Congregational Song'', GIA Publications, {{ISBN|1-57999-100-9}}\n* Bindas, Kenneth J., (1992) ''America's Musical Pulse: Popular Music in Twentieth-Century Society'', Praeger.\n* [[Donald Clarke (writer)|Clarke, Donald]], (1995) ''The Rise and Fall of Popular Music'', St Martin's Press. [https://web.archive.org/web/20071231045026/http://www.musicweb.uk.net/RiseandFall/index.htm ]\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (1999) ''Valuing Pop Music: Institutions, Values and Economics'', Eburon.\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (2004) ''Institutional Economics and the Formation of Preferences: The Advent of Pop Music'', Edward Elgar Publishing.\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]], Straw, Will, Street, John, eds, (2001), ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'', Cambridge University Press,\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]] (2004) ''Popular Music: Critical Concepts in Media and Cultural Studies'', Routledge.\n* [[Charlie Gillett|Gillett, Charlie]], (1970) ''The Sound of the City. The Rise of Rock and Roll'', Outerbridge & Dienstfrey.\n* Hatch, David and Stephen Millward, (1987), ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', Manchester University Press, {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}\n* Johnson, Julian, (2002) ''Who Needs Classical Music?: Cultural Choice and Musical Value'', Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0-19-514681-6}}.\n* [[Jeff Kent (author)|Kent, Jeff]], (1983) ''The Rise and Fall of Rock'', Witan Books, {{ISBN|0-9508981-0-4}}.\n* Lonergan, David F., (2004) ''Hit Records, 1950\u20131975'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0-8108-5129-6}}.\n* Maultsby, Portia K., (7907) ''Intra- and International Identities in American Popular Music'', Trading Culture.\n* [[Richard Middleton (musicologist)|Middleton, Richard]], (1990) ''Studying Popular Music'', Open University Press.\n* Negus, Bob, (1999) ''Music Genres and Corporate Cultures'', Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17399-X}}.\n* [[Henry Pleasants (music critic)|Pleasants, Henry]] (1969) ''Serious Music and All That Jazz'', Simon & Schuster.\n* [[Lillian Roxon|Roxon, Lillian]], (1969) ''Rock Encyclopedia'', Grosset & Dunlap.\n* Shuker, Roy, (2002) ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', Routledge, (2nd edn.) {{ISBN|0-415-28425-2}}.\n* Starr, Larry & Waterman, Christopher, (2002) ''American Popular Music: From Minstrelsy to MTV'', Oxford University Press.\n* Watkins, S. Craig, (2005) ''Hip Hop Matters: Politics, Pop Culture, and the Struggle for the Soul of a Movement'', Beacon Press, {{ISBN|0-8070-0982-2}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Pop music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407053620/http://musiclife.mobi/filelist/1017/sabrang_%282017%29_mp3/new2old/1 The Consumption of Music and the Expression of Values: A Social Economic Explanation for the Advent of Pop Music], Wilfred Dolfsma, ''[[American Journal of Economics and Sociology]]'', October 1999.\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Media culture}}\n{{Western world}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pop Music}}\n[[Category:Pop music| ]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a specific music genre|popular music in general|Popular music|other uses|Pop music (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Pop song|other uses|Pop Song (disambiguation){{!}}Pop Song}}\n{{short description|Genre of popular music which originated in its modern form in the late-1950s deriving from rock and roll}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Pop\n| color = pink\n| bgcolor = #87CEEB\n| stylistic_origins = \n* [[Traditional pop music|Traditional pop]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/subgenre/traditional-pop-ma0000002961/artists  Traditional Pop, ''Allmusic.com''].  Retrieved 25 August 2016</ref>\n* [[rock and roll]]<ref name=Grove/>\n* [[Contemporary folk music|folk]]<ref name=pc1/>\n| cultural_origins = Mid-1950s,<ref name=Firth2001/> United States and United Kingdom\n| image = \n| caption = mj\n| derivatives = * [[Disco]]\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| instruments = \n| subgenrelist = List of pop music genres\n| subgenres = * [[Art pop]]\n* [[Brill Building (genre)|Brill Building]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[experimental pop]]\n* [[hypnagogic pop]]\n* [[new wave]]\n* [[operatic pop]]\n* [[orchestral pop]]\n* [[progressive pop]]\n* [[sophisti-pop]]\n* [[space age pop]]\n* [[sunshine pop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[teen pop]]\n* pop-ballad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/pop-ballad|title=Pop ballad &#124; sentimental song|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3814513|title=Genre and the Ballad|author=Seeger, Judith|year=1994|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|volume=31|issue=1/3|pages=151\u2013176|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n| fusiongenres = * [[Baroque pop]]\n* [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]]\n* [[country pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[noise pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[psychedelic pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[reggae fusion]]\n* [[smooth jazz]]\n* [[smooth soul]]\n| regional_scenes = * [[C-pop|China]]\n* [[Indian pop|India]]\n* [[Indo pop|Indonesia]]\n* [[Cantopop|Hong Kong]]\n* [[Italian popular music#Contemporary Music|Italy]]\n* [[J-pop|Japan]]\n* [[K-pop|Korea]]\n* [[Malaysian pop|Malaysia]]\n* [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]]\n* [[Moroccan pop|Morocco]]\n* [[Pakistani pop music|Pakistan]]\n* [[P-pop|Philippines]]\n* [[Russian pop|Russia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Scandinavia]]\n* [[Swedish pop music|Sweden]]\n* [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]]\n* [[Thai pop music|Thailand]]\n* [[Turkish pop music|Turkey]]\n* [[British pop music|United Kingdom]]\n* [[American pop|United States]]\n* [[V-pop|Vietnam]]\n* [[Europop|Western Europe]]\n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Avant-pop]]\n* [[pop music automation]]\n* [[poptimism]]\n* [[rock music]]\n| current_year = no\n}}\n'''Pop music''' is a genre of [[popular music]] that originated in its modern forms in the [[United States|US]] and the [[United Kingdom|UK]] during the mid-1950s.<ref name=Firth2001/> The terms \"popular music\" and \"pop music\" are often used interchangeably, although the former describes all music that is popular and includes many diverse styles. \"Pop\" and \"[[Rock music|rock]]\" were roughly synonymous terms until the late 1960s, when they became quite separated from each other.\n\nAlthough much of the music that appears on [[record chart]]s is seen as pop music, the genre is distinguished from chart music. Pop music often borrows elements from other styles such as [[urban contemporary|urban]], [[dance music|dance]], [[rock music|rock]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[country music|country]]; nevertheless, there are many key elements that define pop music. Identifying factors usually include short to medium-length songs written in a basic format (often the [[verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus structure]]), as well as common use of repeated choruses, melodic tunes and [[hook (music)|hooks]].\n\n==Definitions and etymology{{anchor|Etymology}}==\n[[File:The Beatles in America.JPG|thumb|left|The 1960s [[British Invasion]] marked a period when the US charts were inundated with British acts such as [[the Beatles]] (pictured 1964).]]\n\nDavid Hatch and Stephen Millward define pop music as \"a body of music which is distinguishable from popular, jazz, and folk musics\".<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1987), {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 1.</ref>\nAccording to [[Pete Seeger]], pop music is \"professional music which draws upon both folk music and fine arts music\".<ref name=pc1>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19745/m1/ |title=Show 1 \u2013 Play A Simple Melody: Pete Seeger on the origins of pop music}}</ref>\nAlthough pop music is seen as just the [[record chart|singles charts]], it is not the sum of all chart music. The music charts contain songs from a variety of sources, including [[classical music|classical]], [[jazz]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[novelty song]]s. As a genre, pop music is seen to exist and develop separately.<ref>R. Serge Denisoff and William L. Schurk, ''Tarnished Gold: the Record Industry Revisited'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, 3rd edn., 1986), {{ISBN|0-88738-618-0}}, pp. 2\u20133.</ref> Therefore, the term \"pop music\" may be used to describe a distinct genre, designed to appeal to all, often characterized as \"instant singles-based music aimed at teenagers\" in contrast to rock music as \"album-based music for adults\".<ref name=Firth2001/>{{refn|Musicologist Allan Moore surmises that the term \"pop music\" itself may have been popularized by [[Pop art]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan F.|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}</ref>}}\n\nPop music continuously evolves along with the term's definition. According to music writer Bill Lamb, popular music is defined as \"the music since industrialization in the 1800s that is most in line with the tastes and interests of the urban middle class.\"<ref name=\"What Is Pop Music\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-pop-music-3246980|title=What Is Pop Music?|access-date=|last = Lamb |first =Bill|website = ThoughtCo.|date = 29 September 2018 }}</ref> The term \"pop song\" was first used in 1926, in the sense of a piece of music \"having popular appeal\".<ref name=OED>J. Simpson and E. Weiner, ''Oxford English Dictionary''(Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989). {{ISBN|0-19-861186-2}}, cf. pop.</ref> Hatch and Millward indicate that many events in the history of recording in the 1920s can be seen as the birth of the modern pop music industry, including in [[country music|country]], [[blues]], and [[hillbilly music]].<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 49.</ref>\n\n[[File: Rolling stones - 11 luglio 2006 - san siro.jpg|thumb|right|''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that the term \"pop\" refers to music performed by such artists as  [[the Rolling Stones]] (pictured here in a 2006 performance).]]\n\nAccording to the website of ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians]]'', the term \"pop music\" \"originated in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in the mid-1950s as a description for [[rock and roll]] and the new youth music styles that it influenced\".<ref name=Grove>R. Middleton, et al., [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_gmo \"Pop\"], ''Grove music online'', retrieved 14 March 2010. {{Subscription required}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that while pop's \"earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience [...] since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus[ic], usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[ABBA]], etc.\"<ref>\"Pop\", [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_t237 ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music''], retrieved 9 March 2010.{{Subscription required}}</ref> ''Grove Music Online'' also states that \"[...] in the early 1960s, [the term] 'pop music' competed terminologically with [[beat music]] [in England], while in the US its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of 'rock and roll'\".<ref name=Grove/>\n\nFrom about 1967, the term \u201cpop music\u201d was increasingly used in opposition to the term [[rock music]], a division that gave generic significance to both terms.<ref name=Gloag983>Kenneth Gloag in ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-19-866212-2}}, p. 983.</ref> While rock aspired to [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]] and an expansion of the possibilities of popular music,<ref name=Gloag983/> pop was more commercial, ephemeral, and accessible.<ref name=Warner2003>T. Warner, ''Pop Music: Technology and Creativity: Trevor Horn and the Digital Revolution'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003), {{ISBN|0-7546-3132-X}}, pp.&nbsp;3\u20134.</ref> According to British musicologist [[Simon Frith]], pop music is produced \"as a matter of [[business|enterprise]] not art\", and is \"designed to appeal to everyone\" but \"doesn't come from any particular place or mark off any particular taste\". Frith adds that it is \"not driven by any significant ambition except profit and commercial reward [...] and, in musical terms, it is essentially conservative\". It is, \"provided from on high (by record companies, radio programmers, and concert promoters) rather than being made from below&nbsp;... Pop is not a [[DIY|do-it-yourself]] music but is professionally produced and packaged\".<ref name=\"Firth2001\"/> {{clear}}\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Elvis_Presley_-_TV_Radio_Mirror,_March_1957_01.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Elvis Presley]]]]\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Righteous Brothers - You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'.ogg\n | title       = The Righteous Brothers \u2013 \"You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'\" (1965)\n | pos         = right\n | description ={{As of|2011}}, \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" ranks as the most frequently played song in US radio history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15186967 |title=Van's Brown Eyed Girl hits the 10 million mark in US|date=5 October 2011 |work=BBC }}</ref> It is described by music writers [[Nick Logan]] and [[Bob Woffinden]] as \"the ultimate pop record\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings, Volume 2|author=Steve Sullivan|pages=101\u2013103 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2013 |isbn= 978-0-8108-8296-6 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to Frith, characteristics of pop music include an aim of appealing to a general audience, rather than to a particular sub-culture or ideology, and an emphasis on craftsmanship rather than formal \"artistic\" qualities.<ref name=Firth2001/> Music scholar Timothy Warner said it typically has an emphasis on recording, production, and technology, rather than live performance; a tendency to reflect existing trends rather than [[progressive music|progressive developments]]; and aims to encourage dancing or uses dance-oriented rhythms.<ref name=Warner2003/>\n\nThe main medium of pop music is the song, often between two and a half and three and a half minutes in length, generally marked by a consistent and noticeable [[rhythm|rhythmic element]], a mainstream style and a simple traditional [[song structure (popular music)|structure]].<ref>W. Everett, ''Expression in Pop-rock Music: A Collection of Critical and Analytical Essays'' (London: Taylor & Francis, 2000), p. 272.</ref> Common variants include the verse-chorus form and the [[thirty-two-bar form]], with a focus on [[melody|melodies]] and catchy [[hook (music)|hooks]], and a [[refrain|chorus]] that contrasts melodically, rhythmically and [[harmony|harmonically]] with the [[Verse (music)|verse]].<ref>J. Shepherd, ''Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World: Performance and production'' (Continuum, 2003), p. 508.</ref> The beat and the melodies tend to be simple, with limited harmonic accompaniment.<ref>V. Kramarz, ''The Pop Formulas: Harmonic Tools of the Hit Makers'' (Mel Bay Publications, 2007), p. 61.</ref> The lyrics of modern pop songs typically focus on simple themes&nbsp;\u2013 often love and romantic relationships&nbsp;\u2013 although there are notable exceptions.<ref name=Firth2001/>\n\n[[Harmony (music)|Harmony]] and [[chord progression]]s in pop music are often \"that of [[Classical music|classical]] European [[tonality]], only more simple-minded.\"<ref>Winkler, Peter (1978). \"Toward a theory of pop harmony\", ''In Theory Only'', 4, pp.&nbsp;3\u201326.</ref> Clich\u00e9s include the [[close and open harmony|barbershop quartet-style harmony]] (i.e. ii \u2013 V \u2013 I) and [[blues scale]]-influenced harmony.<ref>Sargeant, p. 198. cited in Winkler (1978), p. 4.</ref> There was a lessening of the influence of traditional views of the [[circle of fifths]] between the mid-1950s and the late 1970s, including less predominance for the [[dominant (music)|dominant]] [[diatonic function|function]].<ref>Winkler (1978), p. 22.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Development and influence==\n\n===Technology and media===\n\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 230\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson in 1988.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Madonna, Rotterdam, 26-8-1987.jpg\n| width2 = \n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Michael Jackson]] (left) and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (right), known respectively as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King and Queen of Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=April 17, 2013|title=Madonna Pop Art}}</ref>\n| direction = \n}}\n\nIn the 1940s improved [[microphone]] design allowed a more intimate singing style and ten or twenty years later, inexpensive and more durable 45 rpm records for singles \"revolutionized the manner in which pop has been disseminated\", which helped to move pop music to \"a record/radio/film star system\".<ref name=Buckley>D. Buckley, \"Pop\" \"II. Implications of technology\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 15 March 2010.</ref> Another technological change was the widespread availability of television in the 1950s; with televised performances, \"pop stars had to have a visual presence\".<ref name=Buckley/> In the 1960s, the introduction of inexpensive, portable [[transistor radio]]s meant that teenagers in the developed world could listen to music outside of the home.<ref name=Buckley/> By the early 1980s, the promotion of pop music had been greatly affected by the rise of music television channels like [[MTV]], which \"favoured those artists such as [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] who had a strong visual appeal\".<ref name=Buckley/>\n\n[[Multi-track recording]] (from the 1960s); and [[sampling (music)|digital sampling]] (from the 1980s) have also been utilized as methods for the creation and elaboration of pop music.<ref name=Firth2001/> During the mid-1960s, pop music made repeated forays into new sounds, styles, and techniques that inspired public discourse among its listeners. The word \"progressive\" was frequently used, and it was thought that every song and single was to be a \"progression\" from the last.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2|page=162}}</ref> [[Music journalism|Music critic]] [[Simon Reynolds]] writes that beginning with 1967, a divide would exist between \"progressive\" pop and \"mass/chart\" pop, a separation which was \"also, broadly, one between boys and girls, middle-class and working-class.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath|page=398}}</ref>\n\nThe latter half of the 20th-century included a large-scale trend in American culture in which the boundaries between art and pop music were increasingly blurred.<ref>{{cite book|pp=317, 1233|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}</ref> Between 1950 and 1970, there was a debate of pop versus art.<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\"/> Since then, certain music publications have embraced the music's legitimacy, a trend referred to as \"[[poptimism]]\".<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\">{{cite web|last1=Loss|first1=Robert|title=No Apologies: A Critique of the Rockist v. Poptimist Paradigm|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/196122-no-apologies-a-critique-of-the-rockist-v.-poptimist-paradigm/|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stylistic evolution===\n[[File:Katy_Perry_2011.jpg|thumb|left|[[Katy Perry]]'s characteristic spinning peppermint swirl dress which she wore during the California Dreams tour|alt=]]\n\nThroughout its development, pop music has absorbed influences from other genres of popular music. Early pop music drew on the [[sentimental ballad]] for its form, gained its use of vocal harmonies from [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[soul music]], instrumentation from [[jazz]] and [[rock music]], orchestration from [[classical music]], tempo from [[dance music]], backing from [[electronic music]], rhythmic elements from [[hip-hop music]], and spoken passages from [[rap music|rap]].<ref name=Firth2001>S. Frith, W. Straw, and J. Street, eds, ''[[Cambridge Companions to Music|The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013105.</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}} In 2016, a ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' study that examined over 464,000 recordings of popular music recorded between 1955 and 2010 found that since the 1960s, pop music had found less variety in pitch progressions, grown average loudness levels,<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep00521|pmid=22837813|pmc=3405292|title=Measuring the Evolution of Contemporary Western Popular Music|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=2|pages=521|year=2012|last1=Serr\u00e0|first1=Joan|last2=Corral|first2=\u00c1lvaro|last3=Bogu\u00f1\u00e1|first3=Mari\u00e1n|last4=Haro|first4=Mart\u00edn|last5=Arcos|first5=Josep Ll.}}</ref> less diverse instrumentation and recording techniques, and less timbral variety.<ref name=\"Matson\"/> ''[[Scientific American]]''{{'}}s John Matson reported that this \"seems to support the popular anecdotal observation that pop music of yore was \"better\", or at least more varied, than today's top-40 stuff\". However, he also noted that the study may not have been entirely representative of pop in each generation.<ref name=\"Matson\">[http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/is-pop-music-evolving-or-is-it-just-getting-louder/ John Matson, \"Is Pop Music Evolving, or Is It Just Getting Louder?\", ''Scientific American'', 26 July 2012]. Retrieved 30 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the majority of mainstream pop music fell in two categories: guitar, drum and bass groups or singers backed by a traditional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Arrangements\u2014A Rough Guide To Song Construction & Arrangement, Part 1 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |work=Sound on Sound |accessdate=8 May 2014 |date=October 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508082609/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> Since early in the decade, it was common for pop producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with musical form, [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6|page=45}}</ref> At the same time, pop music on radio and in both American and British film moved away from refined [[Tin Pan Alley]] to more eccentric songwriting and incorporated reverb-drenched rock guitar, symphonic strings, and horns played by groups of properly arranged and rehearsed studio musicians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/arts/music/01pupp.html?_r=0|title=Orchestral Pop, the Way It Was (More or Less)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref>  A 2019 study held by [[New York University]] in which 643 participants had to rank how familiar a pop song is to them, songs from the 1960s turned out to be the most memorable, significantly more than songs from recent years 2000 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/news/music/best-decade-pop-music/|title=The greatest decade for pop music has been revealed (according to science)|website=Smooth|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[progressive pop]] of the late 1960s, performers were typically unable to decide on the artistic content of their music.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7|page=217}}</ref> Assisted by the mid-1960s economic boom, record labels began investing in artists, giving them the freedom to experiment, and offering them limited control over their content and marketing.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} This situation declined after the late 1970s and would not reemerge until the rise of [[Internet]] stars.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} [[Indie pop]], which developed in the late 1970s, marked another departure from the glamour of contemporary pop music, with guitar bands formed on the then-novel premise that one could record and release their own music without having to procure a [[record contract]] from a major label.<ref>{{Citation|title=Twee as Fuck: The Story of Indie Pop |first=Nitsuh |last=Abebe |work=Pitchfork Media |date=24 October 2005 |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wjlLnVho?url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Latin pop]] rose in popularity in the [[United States]] during the 1950s with early rock and roll success [[Ritchie Valens]], though it truly rose to prominence during the 1970s and 1980s with the likes of [[Los Lobos]].<ref name=\"Portwood Portwood 2019\">{{cite web | last=Portwood | first=Jerry | last2=Portwood | first2=Jerry | title=Ritchie Valens Musical in the Works From Los Lobos' Louie Perez and David Hidalgo | website=Rolling Stone | date=December 12, 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/ritchie-valens-musical-los-lobos-925326/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With later [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] seeing success within pop music charts, 1990s pop successes stayed popular in both their original genres and in broader pop music. Artists like [[Selena]] saw large-scale pop music presence, and crossover appeal with fans of [[Tejano music]] trailblazers like [[Lydia Mendoza]]; likewise in other genres like [[Lorenzo Antonio]] and [[Sparx (US band)|Sparx]], who are recognized throughout [[Latin America]] as well as within their [[New Mexico music]] repertoire of [[Al Hurricane]] and [[Antonia Apodaca]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Aldama | first=A.J. | last2=Sandoval | first2=C. | last3=Garc\u00eda | first3=P.J. | title=Performing the US Latina and Latino Borderlands | publisher=Indiana University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-253-00295-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7KXaqig1YwC&pg=PA224 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | page=224}}</ref> Musicians like [[Shakira]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Demi Lovato]] seen lasting mass-appeal within pop music circles. Latin pop hit singles, like \u201c[[Macarena]]\u201d by [[Los del R\u00edo]] and \u201c[[Despacito]]\u201d by [[Luis Fonsi]] have seen record-breaking success on worldwide pop music charts.<ref name=\"Villafa\u00f1e 2017\">{{cite web | last=Villafa\u00f1e | first=Veronica | title=Still No.1, Record-Breaking 'Despacito' Ties 'Macarena' Streak On Hot 100, But Is Snubbed By MTV | website=Forbes | date=August 14, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2017/08/14/still-no-1-record-breaking-despacito-ties-macarena-streak-on-hot-100-but-is-snubbed-by-mtv/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980s are commonly remembered for an increase in the use of [[digital recording]], associated with the usage of [[synthesizer]]s, with [[synth-pop]] music and other [[electronic music|electronic]] genres featuring non-traditional instruments increasing in popularity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/29/arts/rap-music-brash-and-swaggering-enters-mainstream.html | work=The New York Times | first=Glenn | last=Collins | title=Rap Music, Brash And Swaggering, Enters Mainstream | date=1988-08-29}}</ref> By 2014, pop music worldwide had been permeated by [[electronic dance music]].<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In 2018, researchers at the [[University of California, Irvine]], concluded that pop music has become 'sadder' since the 1980s. The elements of [[happiness]] and brightness have eventually been replaced with the electronic beats making the pop music more 'sad yet danceable'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/16/sadness-in-pop-music-study|title=New study finds pop music has gotten extremely depressing but also more fun to dance to|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = The story of pop music is largely the story of the intertwining pop culture of the United States and the United Kingdom in the postwar era.\n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 [[Bob Stanley (musician)|Bob Stanley]]<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2014|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/bn2014-07.php|title=Anti-Rockism's Hall of Fame|work=[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor =\n |width = 22%\n |salign = right\n |align = right\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 89%\n}}\n\nPop music has been dominated by the American and (from the mid-1960s) British [[music industry|music industries]], whose influence has made pop music something of an international monoculture, but most regions and countries have their own form of pop music, sometimes producing local versions of wider trends, and lending them local characteristics.<ref>J. Kun, ''Audiotopia: Music, Race, and America'' (Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0-520-24424-9}}, p. 201.</ref> Some of these trends (for example [[Europop]]) have had a significant impact of the development of the genre.<ref name=Firth2002>\"Star profiles\" in S. Frith, W. Stray and J. Street, ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp. 199\u2013200.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Grove Music Online'', \"Western-derived pop styles, whether coexisting with or marginalizing distinctively local genres, have spread throughout the world and have come to constitute stylistic common denominators in global commercial music cultures\".<ref name=PManuel>P. Manuel, \"Pop. Non-Western cultures 1. Global dissemination\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 14 March 2010.</ref> Some non-Western countries, such as Japan, have developed a thriving pop music industry, most of which is devoted to Western-style pop. Japan has for several years produced a greater quantity of music than everywhere except the US.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}}<ref name=PManuel/> The spread of Western-style pop music has been interpreted variously as representing processes of Americanization, [[Radio Homogenization|homogenization]], modernization, creative appropriation, [[cultural imperialism]], or a more general process of [[globalization]].<ref name=PManuel/>\n\nIn Korea, pop music's influence has led to the birth of [[boy bands]] and [[girl groups]] which have gained overseas renown through both their music and aesthetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/yodona/2015/12/03/565f220b46163ff4308b45c9.html|title=K-Pop, la m\u00fasica y la moda 'rarita' coreana que arrasa la red|date=December 3, 2015|website=ELMUNDO}}</ref> Korean [[co-ed groups]] (mixed gender groups) have not been as successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2016/08/25/why-arent-there-many-mixed-gender-k-pop-groups|title=Why aren't there many mixed gender K-pop groups?|website=SBS PopAsia}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pop music|Music}}\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[Origins of rock and roll]]\n* [[Popular music pedagogy]]\n* [[List of popular music genres]]\n* [[History of music]]\n* [[Public domain music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno|Adorno, Theodor W.]], (1942) \"On Popular Music\", Institute of Social Research.\n* Bell, John L., (2000) ''The Singing Thing: A Case for Congregational Song'', GIA Publications, {{ISBN|1-57999-100-9}}\n* Bindas, Kenneth J., (1992) ''America's Musical Pulse: Popular Music in Twentieth-Century Society'', Praeger.\n* [[Donald Clarke (writer)|Clarke, Donald]], (1995) ''The Rise and Fall of Popular Music'', St Martin's Press. [https://web.archive.org/web/20071231045026/http://www.musicweb.uk.net/RiseandFall/index.htm ]\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (1999) ''Valuing Pop Music: Institutions, Values and Economics'', Eburon.\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (2004) ''Institutional Economics and the Formation of Preferences: The Advent of Pop Music'', Edward Elgar Publishing.\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]], Straw, Will, Street, John, eds, (2001), ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'', Cambridge University Press,\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]] (2004) ''Popular Music: Critical Concepts in Media and Cultural Studies'', Routledge.\n* [[Charlie Gillett|Gillett, Charlie]], (1970) ''The Sound of the City. The Rise of Rock and Roll'', Outerbridge & Dienstfrey.\n* Hatch, David and Stephen Millward, (1987), ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', Manchester University Press, {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}\n* Johnson, Julian, (2002) ''Who Needs Classical Music?: Cultural Choice and Musical Value'', Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0-19-514681-6}}.\n* [[Jeff Kent (author)|Kent, Jeff]], (1983) ''The Rise and Fall of Rock'', Witan Books, {{ISBN|0-9508981-0-4}}.\n* Lonergan, David F., (2004) ''Hit Records, 1950\u20131975'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0-8108-5129-6}}.\n* Maultsby, Portia K., (7907) ''Intra- and International Identities in American Popular Music'', Trading Culture.\n* [[Richard Middleton (musicologist)|Middleton, Richard]], (1990) ''Studying Popular Music'', Open University Press.\n* Negus, Bob, (1999) ''Music Genres and Corporate Cultures'', Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17399-X}}.\n* [[Henry Pleasants (music critic)|Pleasants, Henry]] (1969) ''Serious Music and All That Jazz'', Simon & Schuster.\n* [[Lillian Roxon|Roxon, Lillian]], (1969) ''Rock Encyclopedia'', Grosset & Dunlap.\n* Shuker, Roy, (2002) ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', Routledge, (2nd edn.) {{ISBN|0-415-28425-2}}.\n* Starr, Larry & Waterman, Christopher, (2002) ''American Popular Music: From Minstrelsy to MTV'', Oxford University Press.\n* Watkins, S. Craig, (2005) ''Hip Hop Matters: Politics, Pop Culture, and the Struggle for the Soul of a Movement'', Beacon Press, {{ISBN|0-8070-0982-2}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Pop music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407053620/http://musiclife.mobi/filelist/1017/sabrang_%282017%29_mp3/new2old/1 The Consumption of Music and the Expression of Values: A Social Economic Explanation for the Advent of Pop Music], Wilfred Dolfsma, ''[[American Journal of Economics and Sociology]]'', October 1999.\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Media culture}}\n{{Western world}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pop Music}}\n[[Category:Pop music| ]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n", "name_user": "217.171.202.223", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacteristics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pop_music"}
{"title_page": "Daniele Orsato", "text_new": "{{Infobox football official\n| name            = Daniele Orsato\n| image           = Daniele Orsato 2016.jpg\n| caption         = Orsato in 2016\n| full_name       = Daniele Orsato\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|11|23}}\n| birth_place     = [[Vicenza]], Italy\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| years1          = \n| league1         = [[Serie A]]\n| role1           = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2010\u2013\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Daniele Orsato''' (born 23 November 1975 in [[Montecchio Maggiore]])<ref>[http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?contextType=bio&linkType=referee&linkID=4203 Profile]</ref> is an Italian [[association football|football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]].\n\nOrsato became a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]] referee in 2010.<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=ita/footballofficials/referees/peoplekind=ref.html \"Italy: Referees\"]. Retrieved on 17 May 2013.</ref> He has served as a referee in qualifying matches for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 World Cup]]<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/europe/matches/round=258374/match=300182358/report.html \"Match Report - Moldova - Montenegro 0:1 (0:0)\"]. 22 March 2013. Retrieved on 17 May 2013.</ref> and [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualification|Euro 2012]].<ref>UEFA. [http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002268/postmatch/lineups/index.html \"Georgia 1-2 Greece\"]. 11 October 2011. Retrieved on 17 May 2013.</ref>\n\nOrsato refereed group stage matches in the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|2012\u201313]], [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|2013\u201314]], and [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League]] competitions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://worldreferee.com/referee/orsato|title=Palmares for Daniele Orsato|website=WorldrReferee.com|access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Orsato refereed the round of 16 match between [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Atletico Madrid]] in the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 14 March 2017, Orsato refereed the round of 16 match between [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2017/03/12/champions/1489333597_347846.html|title=Orsato pitar\u00e1 en Leicester: con \u00e9l, el Sevilla gan\u00f3 en Villarreal|website=AS.com|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> and was highly praised for his performance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-4314346/Daniele-Orsato-huge-calls-correct.html|title=Referee Daniele Orsato made some huge calls that were absolutely correct in Leicester's victory over Sevilla|work=Daily Mail|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2018, Orsato was appointed a VAR referee for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] match between Croatia and Denmark.\n\nOn February 12, 2019, Orsato refereed the round of 16 first leg match between [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Matches|Manchester United and PSG]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]]. He gave out 10 yellow cards (6 for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and 4 for [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|PSG]]) and sent off [[Paul Pogba]] in the 89th minute.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{UEFA Elite Referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orsato, Daniele}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vicenza]]\n[[Category:Italian football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League referees]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n\n\n{{Italy-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football official\n| officialname    = Daniele Orsato\n| image           = Daniele Orsato 2016.jpg\n| fullname        = Daniele Orsato\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|11|23}}\n| birth_place     = [[Vicenza]], Italy\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| years1          = \n| league1         = [[Serie A]]\n| role1           = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2010\u2013\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Daniele Orsato''' (born 23 November 1975 in [[Montecchio Maggiore]])<ref>[http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?contextType=bio&linkType=referee&linkID=4203 Profile]</ref> is an Italian [[association football|football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]]. \n\nOrsato became a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]] referee in 2010.<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=ita/footballofficials/referees/peoplekind=ref.html \"Italy: Referees\"]. Retrieved on 17 May 2013.</ref> He has served as a referee in qualifying matches for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 World Cup]]<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/europe/matches/round=258374/match=300182358/report.html \"Match Report - Moldova - Montenegro 0:1 (0:0)\"]. 22 March 2013. Retrieved on 17 May 2013.</ref> and [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualification|Euro 2012]].<ref>UEFA. [http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002268/postmatch/lineups/index.html \"Georgia 1-2 Greece\"]. 11 October 2011. Retrieved on 17 May 2013.</ref>\n\nOrsato refereed group stage matches in the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|2012\u201313]], [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|2013\u201314]], and [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League]] competitions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://worldreferee.com/referee/orsato|title=Palmares for Daniele Orsato|website=WorldrReferee.com|access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Orsato refereed the round of 16 match between [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Atletico Madrid]] in the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 14 March 2017, Orsato refereed the round of 16 match between [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2017/03/12/champions/1489333597_347846.html|title=Orsato pitar\u00e1 en Leicester: con \u00e9l, el Sevilla gan\u00f3 en Villarreal|website=AS.com|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> and was highly praised for his performance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-4314346/Daniele-Orsato-huge-calls-correct.html|title=Referee Daniele Orsato made some huge calls that were absolutely correct in Leicester's victory over Sevilla|work=Daily Mail|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2018, Orsato was appointed a VAR referee for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] match between Croatia and Denmark.\n\nOn February 12, 2019, Orsato refereed the round of 16 first leg match between [[2018\u201319_UEFA_Champions_League_knockout_phase#Matches|Manchester United and PSG]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]]. He gave out 10 yellow cards (6 for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and 4 for [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|PSG]]) and sent off [[Paul Pogba]] in the 89th minute.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{UEFA Elite Referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orsato, Daniele}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vicenza]]\n[[Category:Italian football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League referees]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n\n{{Italy-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update infobox to remove article from unknown parameter category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniele_Orsato"}
